{"title_page": "Plumen", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Jevin\n| type = Tamang\n| industry = is\n| foundation = a\n| founders = Bum cheek of America\n| location_city = [[London, United Kingdom]]\n| products = Plumen 001, Plumen 002, Drop Hat, Drop Cap, Drop Top\n| services = Energy efficient lighting\n| num_employees = 11-50 employees\n| website = [http://www.plumen.com www.plumen.com]\n}}\n\n[[File:Plumen2.jpg|thumb|Plumen light bulb]]\n[[File:Plumen 002.jpg|thumb|Image from US patent D738,545 S (Plumen 002 LED bulb)]]\n\n'''Plumen''' is a designer low energy lighting company based in London, UK. The Plumen 001, their debut product, is a designer low energy [[Compact fluorescent lamp|compact fluorescent light]]. The design of the Plumen 001 lightbulb is result of collaboration between the Hulger team and designer Samuel Wilkinson. A prototype of the Plumen 001 has been added to [[Museum of Modern Art|MOMA]] permanent design collection,<ref name=\"Plumen MOMA Collection\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/collection/works/110465|title=Nicolas Roope. PLUMEN low-energy lightbulb (Prototype). 2007.|last=<!-- no byline -->|date=<!-- not specified -->|website=MoMA|access-date=27 January 2018}}</ref> and has won [[Brit Insurance Design Awards]] 2011.<ref name=\"Plumen wins Brit Insurance Design Award\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wallpaper.com/lifestyle/2011-dad-award-winners|title=2011 D&AD award winners|last=Byng|first=Malaika|date=20 June 2011|website=Wallpaper|publisher=Time Inc.|access-date=27 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Plumen 001 bulb launched in September 2010 and was joined by the Plumen 002 that was launched on Kickstarter in January 2014. Plumen also produces accessories and shades to be used with their light bulb designs, establishing Plumen as an efficient designer lighting brand that sells in over 75 countries worldwide.\n\n==Product Range==\nThe Plumen 001 is a [[Compact fluorescent lamp|compact fluorescent light]] which uses 11 [[Watt]] to emit up to 680 [[Lumen (unit)|Lumen]] with colour temperature 2700k (warm white light).\n\nThe Plumen 002 is a [[LED lamp]] which uses 4 [[Watt]] to emit up to 245 [[Lumen (unit)|Lumen]] with colour temperature 2200k (very warm white light). \n\nThe Plumen 003  is a [[LED lamp]] which uses 6.5 watts. to emit up to 250 [[Lumen (unit)|Lumen]] with colour temperature 2400k (very warm white light). The bulb was designed in collaboration between Hulger, British industrial designer Claire Norcross and French jewellery designer Marie-Laure Giroux\n\nIn 2016 Plumen also launched a lower cost range of designer filament LED bulbs under the brand WattNott \n\nThe 001 and 002 lamp designs are protected by US patent D665,930 S and US patent US D738,545 S respectively.\n\n==Awards and collections==\n* [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA) Permanent design collection\n* [[Cooper-Hewitt, National Design Museum]] Permanent design collection\n* [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] Permanent collection\n* [[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]] Design and The Elastic Mind exhibition 2008\n* [[The Art Institute of Chicago]]\n* Helsinki Design Museum\n* [[Brit Insurance Design Awards]] Design of the Year Winner 2011\n* [[D&AD Black Pencil]] 2011\n* [[Homes & Gardens 'Eco Product of the Year']] 2011\n* [[Smarta Award 'Innovation']] 2011\n* ''[[GQ]]'' ''Best Stuff of The Year'' 2011\n* [[Elle Deco]] Best Sustainable Design Award 2014 (Plumen 002)\n* ''[[GQ]]'' ''Best Stuff of The Year'' 2014 - Plumen 002 (China edition)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.plumen.com Official Website]\n*[https://lightuk.com/ Outdoor Lighting Product]\n*[http://www.designsoftheyear.com/category/genre/product/product-2011/ Brit Insurance Award 2011]\n*[http://www.moma.org/collection/browse_results.php?criteria=O:DE:I:1|G:HI:E:1&page_number=17&template_id=1&sort_order=2 MOMA Permanent Collection Page]\n*[http://www.fastcompany.com/tag/plumen Coverage] - [[Fast Company (magazine)]]\n\n{{Artificial light sources}}\n\n[[Category:Lighting]]\n[[Category:British design]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Plumen\n| type = Privately held\n| industry = Consumer electronics\n| foundation = 2010\n| founders = [[Nicolas Roope]], Michael-George Hemus and Ronnie Renton\n| location_city = [[London, United Kingdom]]\n| products = Plumen 001, Plumen 002, Drop Hat, Drop Cap, Drop Top\n| services = Energy efficient lighting\n| num_employees = 11-50 employees\n| website = [http://www.plumen.com www.plumen.com]\n}}\n\n[[File:Plumen2.jpg|thumb|Plumen light bulb]]\n[[File:Plumen 002.jpg|thumb|Image from US patent D738,545 S (Plumen 002 LED bulb)]]\n\n'''Plumen''' is a designer low energy lighting company based in London, UK. The Plumen 001, their debut product, is a designer low energy [[Compact fluorescent lamp|compact fluorescent light]]. The design of the Plumen 001 lightbulb is result of collaboration between the Hulger team and designer Samuel Wilkinson. A prototype of the Plumen 001 has been added to [[Museum of Modern Art|MOMA]] permanent design collection,<ref name=\"Plumen MOMA Collection\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/collection/works/110465|title=Nicolas Roope. PLUMEN low-energy lightbulb (Prototype). 2007.|last=<!-- no byline -->|date=<!-- not specified -->|website=MoMA|access-date=27 January 2018}}</ref> and has won [[Brit Insurance Design Awards]] 2011.<ref name=\"Plumen wins Brit Insurance Design Award\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wallpaper.com/lifestyle/2011-dad-award-winners|title=2011 D&AD award winners|last=Byng|first=Malaika|date=20 June 2011|website=Wallpaper|publisher=Time Inc.|access-date=27 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Plumen 001 bulb launched in September 2010 and was joined by the Plumen 002 that was launched on Kickstarter in January 2014. Plumen also produces accessories and shades to be used with their light bulb designs, establishing Plumen as an efficient designer lighting brand that sells in over 75 countries worldwide.\n\n==Product Range==\nThe Plumen 001 is a [[Compact fluorescent lamp|compact fluorescent light]] which uses 11 [[Watt]] to emit up to 680 [[Lumen (unit)|Lumen]] with colour temperature 2700k (warm white light).\n\nThe Plumen 002 is a [[LED lamp]] which uses 4 [[Watt]] to emit up to 245 [[Lumen (unit)|Lumen]] with colour temperature 2200k (very warm white light). \n\nThe Plumen 003  is a [[LED lamp]] which uses 6.5 watts. to emit up to 250 [[Lumen (unit)|Lumen]] with colour temperature 2400k (very warm white light). The bulb was designed in collaboration between Hulger, British industrial designer Claire Norcross and French jewellery designer Marie-Laure Giroux\n\nIn 2016 Plumen also launched a lower cost range of designer filament LED bulbs under the brand WattNott \n\nThe 001 and 002 lamp designs are protected by US patent D665,930 S and US patent US D738,545 S respectively.\n\n==Awards and collections==\n* [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA) Permanent design collection\n* [[Cooper-Hewitt, National Design Museum]] Permanent design collection\n* [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] Permanent collection\n* [[Museum of Modern Art|MoMA]] Design and The Elastic Mind exhibition 2008\n* [[The Art Institute of Chicago]]\n* Helsinki Design Museum\n* [[Brit Insurance Design Awards]] Design of the Year Winner 2011\n* [[D&AD Black Pencil]] 2011\n* [[Homes & Gardens 'Eco Product of the Year']] 2011\n* [[Smarta Award 'Innovation']] 2011\n* ''[[GQ]]'' ''Best Stuff of The Year'' 2011\n* [[Elle Deco]] Best Sustainable Design Award 2014 (Plumen 002)\n* ''[[GQ]]'' ''Best Stuff of The Year'' 2014 - Plumen 002 (China edition)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.plumen.com Official Website]\n*[https://lightuk.com/ Outdoor Lighting Product]\n*[http://www.designsoftheyear.com/category/genre/product/product-2011/ Brit Insurance Award 2011]\n*[http://www.moma.org/collection/browse_results.php?criteria=O:DE:I:1|G:HI:E:1&page_number=17&template_id=1&sort_order=2 MOMA Permanent Collection Page]\n*[http://www.fastcompany.com/tag/plumen Coverage] - [[Fast Company (magazine)]]\n\n{{Artificial light sources}}\n\n[[Category:Lighting]]\n[[Category:British design]]\n", "name_user": "78.148.20.96", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plumen"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Delaware", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Delaware, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Delaware\n| map1            = Number of COVID 19 cases in Delaware.svg\n| legend1         = Counties by number of positive cases in Delaware as of April 20:{{legend|#510000|> 1200 Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#c80200|1000\u20131199 Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|< 999 Confirmed cases}}\n| first_case      = [[New Castle County]]\n| arrival_date    = March 11, 2020\n| confirmed_cases = 2,745\n| recovery_cases  = 495\n| hospitalized_cases = 256\n| deaths          = 72\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Delaware]], U.S.\n| website         = [https://www.dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/dph/epi/2019novelcoronavirus.html Delaware Department of Health and Social Services]\n}}\n\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' was reported to have reached the [[U.S. state]] of '''[[Delaware]]''' on March 11, 2020 in [[New Castle County]]. As of April 20, 2020, the Delaware Department of Health and Social Services has confirmed 2,745 positive cases and 72 deaths in the state, with 495 people being fully recovered.\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Delaware medical cases chart}}\n\n=== March 4 ===\nOn March 4, in preparation for the coronavirus' spread in Delaware, the [[Delaware Division of Public Health]] opened a coronavirus call center at its State Health Operation Center in [[Smyrna, Delaware|Smyrna]] to assist with questions that businesses, schools, and people may have about the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41853374/delaware-division-of-public-health-opens-coronavirus-call-center|title=Delaware Opens Coronavirus Call Center|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n=== March 11\u201313 ===\nOn March 11, the Delaware Division of Public Health announced its first presumptive positive case of coronavirus in Delaware. The positive case involved a man over the age of 50 in [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]] who was associated with the [[University of Delaware]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.delaware.gov/2020/03/11/public-health-announces-first-presumptive-positive-case-of-coronavirus-in-delaware-resident/|title=Public Health Announces First Presumptive Positive Case of Coronavirus in Delaware Resident|date=2020-03-11|website=State of Delaware News|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, Delaware Governor [[John Carney (politician)|John Carney]] declared a state of emergency. This allowed for the [[Delaware National Guard]] to take precautionary actions and prepare for further response to the disease, for the state to conduct public meetings electronically, and prevent the price gouging of goods. Governor Carney also recommended that all non-essential public gatherings of over 100 people be canceled, following CDC guidelines.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41888267/governor-carney-declares-state-of-emergency-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Governor Carney Declares State of Emergency Amidst Coronavirus Outbreak|last=Lu|first=Amy|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> Three more positive cases of coronavirus were confirmed on March 12. The patients were two graduate students and a postdoctoral researcher at the University of Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2020/03/12/coronavirus-university-of-delaware-announces-3-more-members-test-positive-coronavirus-professor-diagnosed/|title=Coronavirus In Delaware: Governor Declares State Of Emergency As 3 More University Of Delaware Members Test Positive For COVID-19|date=2020-03-12|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> [[Delaware State University]] President Dr. Tony Allen advised all students to not return to campus until at least April 5. He also announced that all classes from March 18 until April 5 will take place online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desu.edu/student-life/student-health-services/coronavirus|title=Coronavirus|date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315023946/https://www.desu.edu/student-life/student-health-services/coronavirus|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the Downtown Dover Partnership announced the cancellation of the [[Saint Patrick's Day|St. Patrick's Day]] parade due to coronavirus concerns.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41892567/dover-cancels-permits-for-large-events-in-light-of-covid19-state-of-emergency|title=Dover Cancels Permits for Large Events in Light of COVID-19 State of Emergency|last=Lehman|first=Tom|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> Late on March 13, Governor Carney closed all Delaware Public Schools from March 16 to March 27.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41896010/delaware-schools-on-hiatus-for-two-weeks-due-to-covid19|title=Delaware Schools on Hiatus for Two Weeks Due to COVID-19|last=Semyon|first=Cassandra|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> In addition, the University of Delaware announced that all classes after spring break would be moved to an all-online format for the remainder of the semester. All University of Delaware on-campus housing would close for students who remained on the campus during spring break on March 17 at 10:00 pm and for all students who were returning to campus on March 22 at 10:00 pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.udel.edu/udaily/2020/march/coronavirus-update-march-13-2020/|title=March 13 Coronavirus update: residence halls to close {{!}} UDaily|website=udel.edu|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n=== March 14\u201316 ===\nOn March 14, the Delaware Division of Public Health announced two more positive cases of coronavirus in the state. The two new patients were both self-quarantining in New Castle County: a woman older than 50 and a man older than 60. This increased the number of total positive cases in Delaware to 6.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41895944/dph-announces-2-more-likely-cases-of-covid19-in-delaware|title=DPH Announces 2 More Likely Positive Cases of COVID-19 in Delaware|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nDelaware announced their seventh case in the state on March 15; the case is associated with University of Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://6abc.com/6015929/|title=7th coronavirus case confirmed in Delaware|date=2020-03-15|website=6abc Philadelphia|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Delaware Division of Public Health announced on March 16 that a woman over 50 in New Castle County was confirmed to have coronavirus. The total number of positive cases increased to 8 in Delaware with the addition of this case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmdt.com/2020/03/just-in-eighth-positive-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-delaware-dph-says/|title=JUST IN: Eighth positive coronavirus case confirmed in Delaware, DPH says|date=2020-03-16|website=47abc|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n=== March 17\u201319 ===\nIt was announced on March 17 that eight additional positive cases of coronavirus were confirmed in the state, including the first in [[Sussex County, Delaware|Sussex County]]. Of the patients, four were men and four were women, though their ages have not been revealed. This increased the total number of positive cases to 16 in Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41906635/first-covid19-case-in-sussex-county-reported-state-cases-double|title=First COVID-19 Case in Sussex County Reported, State Cases Double|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, the DDHS announced the addition of 10 more positive cases in the state of Delaware, including the first three in [[Kent County, Delaware|Kent County]]. All three of Delaware's counties had at least one coronavirus case by March 18. The addition of these cases increased the cumulative number of positive cases to 26 for the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41909829/first-coronavirus-case-reported-in-kent-county-del|title=UPDATE: Delaware COVID-19 Cases Rise to 26, Kent and Sussex Record 3 Positive Tests Each|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n[[Dover Air Force Base]] declared a public health emergency on March 18, allowing for tighter restrictions of the movement of people on the base, including personnel restrictions and access restrictions to the base's installation. In addition, the emergency allowed the isolation and quarantine procedures for the base to go into effect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41909048/dover-air-force-base-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Dover Air Force Base Declares Public Health Emergency|last=Kerr|first=Rose|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the number of cases was confirmed to have increased to 30: 23 in New Castle, 3 in Sussex, and 4 in Kent Counties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmdt.com/2020/03/four-additional-cases-announced-in-delaware/|title=Four additional cases announced in Delaware|date=2020-03-19|website=47abc|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n=== March 20\u201322 ===\n\nOn March 20, the state reported 27 lab-confirmed cases of COVID-19 in New Castle County, five in Kent County and seven in Sussex County, which brings the total to 39, with two people being in critical condition.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe Delaware Division of Public Health (DPH) had reported 30 COVID-19 cases in the state just the day before. DPH said testing is recommended for people with a fever and either a cough or shortness of breath.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41921160/first-coronavirus-case-reported-in-kent-county-del|title=Delaware COVID-19 Cases Rise to 38|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\n\n==== March 12 ====\nDelaware Governor John Carney declared a state of emergency on March 12, allowing for the Delaware National Guard to prepare for the coronavirus' spread.<ref name=\":1\" /> He would close all public schools in the state on March 13.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== March 13 ====\nThe City of Dover canceled all permits for event gatherings of over 100 people on March 13, citing the governor's recommendation.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== March 16 ====\nOn March 16, all public libraries within Delaware have been closed until further notice. Restaurants were ordered to stop dine-in services at 8pm EST, moving to to-go and delivery only services. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lib.de.us/letter-from-ala/|title=Letter from ALA|website=Delaware Libraries|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==== March 23 ====\n\nOn March 23, Governor John Carney has issued the [[stay-at-home order]] to stop the spread of COVID-19. All non-essential businesses have been ordered to close. Governor Carney issued the order Sunday night, set to go in effect Tuesday morning at 8 a.m., stating \"All non-essential businesses are closed. All Delawareans are instructed to stay in their homes, except when they are going to and from their place of business if it's permitted to stay open\". This shelter-in-place order will remain in effect until May 15.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41929980/delaware-prepares-for-stay-at-home-order|title=Delaware Prepares for Stay at Home Order|last=Semyon|first=Cassandra|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Additionally, Delaware schools are to remain closed through May 15 to fight the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41930078/delaware-schools-to-remain-closed-through-may-15-to-fight-spread-of-covid19|title=Delaware Schools to Remain Closed Through May 15 to Fight Spread of COVID-19|last=Lehman|first=Tom|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==== April 17 ====\n\nOn April 17, Governor John Carney announced that schools in the state will remain closed until May 18th, with updates coming if necessary. He also mentioned that there is not enough information yet to make a decision regarding the remainder of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmdt.com/2020/04/del-schools-to-remain-closed-until-may-18th-additional-updates-from-gov-carney/|title=Del. schools to remain closed until May 18th, additional updates from Gov. Carney|date=2020-04-17|website=47abc|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] canceled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Delaware<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/dph/epi/2019novelcoronavirus.html|title=2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) - Delaware Health and Social Services - State of Delaware|website=dhss.delaware.gov|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\nUpdated April 20, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle]]\n|1,229\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kent County, Delaware|Kent]]\n|430\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Sussex County, Delaware|Sussex]]\n|1,055\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Unknown\n|31\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |2,735\n|}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/dph/epi/2019novelcoronavirus.html Coronavirus information] from the Delaware Department of Health and Social Services\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|United States|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Delaware]]\n[[Category:2020 in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Health in Delaware]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Delaware, United States}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Delaware\n| map1            = Number of COVID 19 cases in Delaware.svg\n| legend1         = Counties by number of positive cases in Delaware as of April 20:{{legend|#510000|1200+ Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#c80200|1000\u20131199 Confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u2013999 Confirmed cases}}\n| first_case      = [[New Castle County]]\n| arrival_date    = March 11, 2020\n| confirmed_cases = 2,745\n| recovery_cases  = 495\n| hospitalized_cases = 256\n| deaths          = 72\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Delaware]], U.S.\n| website         = [https://www.dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/dph/epi/2019novelcoronavirus.html Delaware Department of Health and Social Services]\n}}\n\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' was reported to have reached the [[U.S. state]] of '''[[Delaware]]''' on March 11, 2020 in [[New Castle County]]. As of April 20, 2020, the Delaware Department of Health and Social Services has confirmed 2,745 positive cases and 72 deaths in the state, with 495 people being fully recovered.\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Delaware medical cases chart}}\n\n=== March 4 ===\nOn March 4, in preparation for the coronavirus' spread in Delaware, the [[Delaware Division of Public Health]] opened a coronavirus call center at its State Health Operation Center in [[Smyrna, Delaware|Smyrna]] to assist with questions that businesses, schools, and people may have about the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41853374/delaware-division-of-public-health-opens-coronavirus-call-center|title=Delaware Opens Coronavirus Call Center|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n=== March 11\u201313 ===\nOn March 11, the Delaware Division of Public Health announced its first presumptive positive case of coronavirus in Delaware. The positive case involved a man over the age of 50 in [[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle County]] who was associated with the [[University of Delaware]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.delaware.gov/2020/03/11/public-health-announces-first-presumptive-positive-case-of-coronavirus-in-delaware-resident/|title=Public Health Announces First Presumptive Positive Case of Coronavirus in Delaware Resident|date=2020-03-11|website=State of Delaware News|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, Delaware Governor [[John Carney (politician)|John Carney]] declared a state of emergency. This allowed for the [[Delaware National Guard]] to take precautionary actions and prepare for further response to the disease, for the state to conduct public meetings electronically, and prevent the price gouging of goods. Governor Carney also recommended that all non-essential public gatherings of over 100 people be canceled, following CDC guidelines.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41888267/governor-carney-declares-state-of-emergency-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Governor Carney Declares State of Emergency Amidst Coronavirus Outbreak|last=Lu|first=Amy|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> Three more positive cases of coronavirus were confirmed on March 12. The patients were two graduate students and a postdoctoral researcher at the University of Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2020/03/12/coronavirus-university-of-delaware-announces-3-more-members-test-positive-coronavirus-professor-diagnosed/|title=Coronavirus In Delaware: Governor Declares State Of Emergency As 3 More University Of Delaware Members Test Positive For COVID-19|date=2020-03-12|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> [[Delaware State University]] President Dr. Tony Allen advised all students to not return to campus until at least April 5. He also announced that all classes from March 18 until April 5 will take place online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.desu.edu/student-life/student-health-services/coronavirus|title=Coronavirus|date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315023946/https://www.desu.edu/student-life/student-health-services/coronavirus|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the Downtown Dover Partnership announced the cancellation of the [[Saint Patrick's Day|St. Patrick's Day]] parade due to coronavirus concerns.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41892567/dover-cancels-permits-for-large-events-in-light-of-covid19-state-of-emergency|title=Dover Cancels Permits for Large Events in Light of COVID-19 State of Emergency|last=Lehman|first=Tom|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> Late on March 13, Governor Carney closed all Delaware Public Schools from March 16 to March 27.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41896010/delaware-schools-on-hiatus-for-two-weeks-due-to-covid19|title=Delaware Schools on Hiatus for Two Weeks Due to COVID-19|last=Semyon|first=Cassandra|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> In addition, the University of Delaware announced that all classes after spring break would be moved to an all-online format for the remainder of the semester. All University of Delaware on-campus housing would close for students who remained on the campus during spring break on March 17 at 10:00 pm and for all students who were returning to campus on March 22 at 10:00 pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.udel.edu/udaily/2020/march/coronavirus-update-march-13-2020/|title=March 13 Coronavirus update: residence halls to close {{!}} UDaily|website=udel.edu|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n=== March 14\u201316 ===\nOn March 14, the Delaware Division of Public Health announced two more positive cases of coronavirus in the state. The two new patients were both self-quarantining in New Castle County: a woman older than 50 and a man older than 60. This increased the number of total positive cases in Delaware to 6.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41895944/dph-announces-2-more-likely-cases-of-covid19-in-delaware|title=DPH Announces 2 More Likely Positive Cases of COVID-19 in Delaware|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nDelaware announced their seventh case in the state on March 15; the case is associated with University of Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://6abc.com/6015929/|title=7th coronavirus case confirmed in Delaware|date=2020-03-15|website=6abc Philadelphia|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Delaware Division of Public Health announced on March 16 that a woman over 50 in New Castle County was confirmed to have coronavirus. The total number of positive cases increased to 8 in Delaware with the addition of this case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmdt.com/2020/03/just-in-eighth-positive-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-delaware-dph-says/|title=JUST IN: Eighth positive coronavirus case confirmed in Delaware, DPH says|date=2020-03-16|website=47abc|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n=== March 17\u201319 ===\nIt was announced on March 17 that eight additional positive cases of coronavirus were confirmed in the state, including the first in [[Sussex County, Delaware|Sussex County]]. Of the patients, four were men and four were women, though their ages have not been revealed. This increased the total number of positive cases to 16 in Delaware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41906635/first-covid19-case-in-sussex-county-reported-state-cases-double|title=First COVID-19 Case in Sussex County Reported, State Cases Double|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, the DDHS announced the addition of 10 more positive cases in the state of Delaware, including the first three in [[Kent County, Delaware|Kent County]]. All three of Delaware's counties had at least one coronavirus case by March 18. The addition of these cases increased the cumulative number of positive cases to 26 for the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41909829/first-coronavirus-case-reported-in-kent-county-del|title=UPDATE: Delaware COVID-19 Cases Rise to 26, Kent and Sussex Record 3 Positive Tests Each|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n[[Dover Air Force Base]] declared a public health emergency on March 18, allowing for tighter restrictions of the movement of people on the base, including personnel restrictions and access restrictions to the base's installation. In addition, the emergency allowed the isolation and quarantine procedures for the base to go into effect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41909048/dover-air-force-base-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Dover Air Force Base Declares Public Health Emergency|last=Kerr|first=Rose|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, the number of cases was confirmed to have increased to 30: 23 in New Castle, 3 in Sussex, and 4 in Kent Counties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmdt.com/2020/03/four-additional-cases-announced-in-delaware/|title=Four additional cases announced in Delaware|date=2020-03-19|website=47abc|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n=== March 20\u201322 ===\n\nOn March 20, the state reported 27 lab-confirmed cases of COVID-19 in New Castle County, five in Kent County and seven in Sussex County, which brings the total to 39, with two people being in critical condition.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe Delaware Division of Public Health (DPH) had reported 30 COVID-19 cases in the state just the day before. DPH said testing is recommended for people with a fever and either a cough or shortness of breath.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41921160/first-coronavirus-case-reported-in-kent-county-del|title=Delaware COVID-19 Cases Rise to 38|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== Government response ==\n\n==== March 12 ====\nDelaware Governor John Carney declared a state of emergency on March 12, allowing for the Delaware National Guard to prepare for the coronavirus' spread.<ref name=\":1\" /> He would close all public schools in the state on March 13.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== March 13 ====\nThe City of Dover canceled all permits for event gatherings of over 100 people on March 13, citing the governor's recommendation.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==== March 16 ====\nOn March 16, all public libraries within Delaware have been closed until further notice. Restaurants were ordered to stop dine-in services at 8pm EST, moving to to-go and delivery only services. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lib.de.us/letter-from-ala/|title=Letter from ALA|website=Delaware Libraries|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==== March 23 ====\n\nOn March 23, Governor John Carney has issued the [[stay-at-home order]] to stop the spread of COVID-19. All non-essential businesses have been ordered to close. Governor Carney issued the order Sunday night, set to go in effect Tuesday morning at 8 a.m., stating \"All non-essential businesses are closed. All Delawareans are instructed to stay in their homes, except when they are going to and from their place of business if it's permitted to stay open\". This shelter-in-place order will remain in effect until May 15.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41929980/delaware-prepares-for-stay-at-home-order|title=Delaware Prepares for Stay at Home Order|last=Semyon|first=Cassandra|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Additionally, Delaware schools are to remain closed through May 15 to fight the spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wboc.com/story/41930078/delaware-schools-to-remain-closed-through-may-15-to-fight-spread-of-covid19|title=Delaware Schools to Remain Closed Through May 15 to Fight Spread of COVID-19|last=Lehman|first=Tom|website=wboc.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==== April 17 ====\n\nOn April 17, Governor John Carney announced that schools in the state will remain closed until May 18th, with updates coming if necessary. He also mentioned that there is not enough information yet to make a decision regarding the remainder of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmdt.com/2020/04/del-schools-to-remain-closed-until-may-18th-additional-updates-from-gov-carney/|title=Del. schools to remain closed until May 18th, additional updates from Gov. Carney|date=2020-04-17|website=47abc|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] canceled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Delaware<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/dph/epi/2019novelcoronavirus.html|title=2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) - Delaware Health and Social Services - State of Delaware|website=dhss.delaware.gov|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\nUpdated April 20, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[New Castle County, Delaware|New Castle]]\n|1,229\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kent County, Delaware|Kent]]\n|430\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Sussex County, Delaware|Sussex]]\n|1,055\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Unknown\n|31\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" |2,735\n|}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.dhss.delaware.gov/dhss/dph/epi/2019novelcoronavirus.html Coronavirus information] from the Delaware Department of Health and Social Services\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|United States|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Delaware]]\n[[Category:2020 in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Health in Delaware]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "CAWylie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Delaware"}
{"title_page": "Snopes", "text_new": "{{for|the novels by William Faulkner|Snopes trilogy}}\n{{short description|Fact-checking website}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = Snopes.com\n| logo             = Snopes logo.png\n| logo_size        = 150px\n| logo_alt         = Snopes logo\n| screenshot       = File:Snopes home page screenshot.png\n| url              = {{URL|https://www.snopes.com}}\n| commercial       = Yes\n| type             = Reference pages\n| registration     = Required only on forums\n| owner            = {{Plainlist|\n*David P. Mikkelson<ref name=webby>{{cite web |url=http://webbyawards.com/lists/how-the-truth-set-snopes-free |website=[[Webby Awards]] | title=How the Truth Set Snopes Free |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n*Proper Media<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|last1=Streitfeld|first1=David|title=For Fact Checking Website Snopes, a Bigger Role Brings More Attacks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/25/technology/for-fact-checking-website-snopes-a-bigger-role-brings-more-attacks.html?_r=0|access-date=December 27, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=December 25, 2016 |url-access=limited}}</ref>\n}}\n| author           = Barbara Mikkelson<br>David P. Mikkelson<ref name=webby />\n| launch_date      = 1994 (as Urban Legends Reference Pages)\n| alexa            = {{IncreaseNegative}}  3,290 (US 693) ({{as of|2018|2|05|alt=February 2019}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/snopes.com|title= Snopes.com Site Info|website=[[Alexa Internet]]|access-date=February 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| current_status   = Active\n}}\n\n'''Snopes''' {{IPAc-en|'|s|n|o\u028a|p|s}}, formerly known as the '''Urban Legends Reference Pages''', is a [[Fact checking|fact-checking]] website.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4819108 |title=Snopes.com: Debunking Myths in Cyberspace] |website=[[NPR]] |date=August 27, 2005 |access-date=August 27, 2005}}</ref> It has been described as a \"well-regarded reference for sorting out myths and rumors\" on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/77880145/ |first=Melissa |last=Allison |title=Companies Find Rumors Hard to Kill on Internet |work=Herald and Review |date= March 4, 2007}} (image 3).</ref><ref>Same article: {{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/359621651 |title=Corporations Combat Insistent Urban Legends on Internet |work=The Courier |date=March 4, 2007}} (image 7).</ref> It has also been seen as a source for validating and [[Debunker|debunking]] [[urban legend]]s and similar stories in [[Culture of the United States|American popular culture]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Henry |first=Neil |title=American Carnival: Journalism Under Siege in an Age of New Media |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780520243422 |url-access=registration |publisher=University of California Press |year=2007 |p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780520243422/page/285 285]| quote=\"The most widely known resource for validating or debunking rumors, myths, hoaxes, and urban legends in popular American culture is the website run by Barbara and David P. Mikkelson at www.snopes.com...\"}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1994,<ref name=\"tri\">{{Cite web|url=https://twit.tv/shows/triangulation/episodes/343|title=Triangulation 343 David Mikkelson, Snopes.com |website=TWiT.tv|language=en-US|access-date=April 25, 2018}}</ref> David and Barbara Mikkelson created an urban [[folklore]] web site that would become Snopes.com. Snopes was an early [[online encyclopedia]] focused on urban legends, that mainly presented search results of user discussions. The site grew to encompass a wide range of subjects and became a resource to which Internet users began submitting pictures and stories of questionable veracity. According to the Mikkelsons, Snopes predated the [[search engine]] concept of fact-checking via search results.<ref name=\"nyt100405\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/05/technology/05snopes.html|title=Debunkers of Fictions Sift the Net|author=[[Brian Stelter]]|date=April 4, 2010|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 5, 2010 |url-access=limited}}</ref> David Mikkelson had originally adopted the username \"Snopes\" (the name of a family of often unpleasant people in the works of [[William Faulkner]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/info/faq.asp#snopes |title=Frequently Asked Questions |quote=What are 'snopes'? |website=Snopes |access-date=June 9, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Chron\">{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Bond |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |title=Web site separates fact from urban legend |url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Web-site-separates-fact-from-urban-legend-2800717.php |date=September 7, 2002 |access-date=July 17, 2012}}</ref> in the [[Usenet]] newsgroup alt.folklore.urban.<ref name=\"Chron\" /><ref name=\"Porter\">{{cite book |last=Porter |first=David |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KQLaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48 |title=Internet Culture |chapter=Usenet Communities and the Cultural Politics of Information |publisher=[[Routledge]] |year=2013 |page=48 |isbn=978-1-135-20904-9 |access-date=September 13, 2016 |quote=The two most notorious trollers in AFU, [[Ted Frank]] and snopes, are also two of the most consistent posters of serious research.}}</ref><ref name=\"Seipp\">{{cite news |first=Cathy |last=Seipp |authorlink=Catherine Seipp |work=[[National Review]] |title=Where Urban Legends Fall |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/seipp/seipp200407210830.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040812075515/http://www.nationalreview.com/seipp/seipp200407210830.asp |archivedate=August 12, 2004 |access-date=February 7, 2014 |date=July 21, 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the site had become known well enough that a [[television pilot]] called ''Snopes: Urban Legends'' was completed with American actor [[Jim Davidson (actor)|Jim Davidson]] as host. However, it did not air on major networks.<ref name=\"Chron\" />\n\nBy mid-2014, Barbara had not written for Snopes \"in several years\"<ref name=\"webby\" /> and David was forced to hire users from Snopes.com's message board to assist him in running the site. The Mikkelsons divorced around that time.<ref name=\"webby\" /><ref name=\"Madrigal_Atlantic\">{{cite news |last1=Madrigal |first1=Alexis C. |title=Snopes Faces an Ugly Legal Battle |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2017/07/the-ugly-dispute-threatening-snopes/534708/ |work=[[The Atlantic]]  |date=July 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Chris Richmond (entrepreneur)|Christopher Richmond]] and Drew Schoentrup became part owners in July of 2016 with the purchase of Barbara Mikkelson's share by the internet media management company Proper Media.<ref name=\"CNS_Bruno\">{{cite news |last1=Bruno |first1=Bianca |title=Fact-Checker Snopes' Owners Accused of Corporate Subterfuge |url=https://www.courthousenews.com/fact-checker-snopes-owners-accused-corporate-subterfuge/ |website=[[Courthouse News Service|Courthouse News]] |date=May 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, 2017, David Mikkelson terminated the brokering agreement with Proper Media, which is also the company that provides Snopes with [[web development]], [[Web hosting service|hosting]], and [[Web advertising|advertising]] support.<ref name=\"WaPoLegal2017\">{{cite news|last1=Farhi|first1=Paul|title=Is Snopes.com, the original Internet fact-checker, going out of business?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/is-snopescom-the-original-internet-fact-checker-going-out-of-business/2017/07/24/8a03d196-708d-11e7-8839-ec48ec4cae25_story.html|work=The Washington Post|date=July 24, 2017}}</ref> This prompted Proper Media to stop remitting advertising revenue and to file a lawsuit in May. In late June, Bardav\u2014the company founded by David and Barbara Mikkelson in 2003 to own and operate snopes.com\u2014started a [[GoFundMe]] campaign to raise money to continue operations.<ref name=\"NYTLegal2017\">{{cite news|last1=Victor|first1=Daniel|title=Snopes, in Heated Legal Battle, Asks Readers for Money to Survive |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/24/business/media/snopes-crowdfunding-proper-media.html |work=The New York Times |date=July 24, 2017 |url-access=limited}}</ref> They raised $500,000 in 24 hours.<ref>{{cite web |title=Snopes Meets $500K Crowdfunding Goal Amid Legal Battle |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-25/snopes-launches-online-fundraiser-amid-legal-battle |website=[[Bloomberg Businessweek|Bloomberg]] |date=July 25, 2017 |access-date=December 18, 2017 |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Later, in August, a judge ordered Proper Media to disburse advertising revenues to Bardav while the case was pending.<ref name=\"WiredSnopes\">{{cite news |last1=Dean |first1=Michelle |title=Snopes and the Search for Facts in a Post-Fact World |url=https://www.wired.com/story/snopes-and-the-search-for-facts-in-a-post-fact-world? |date=September 20, 2017 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2019, Snopes announced that it had acquired the website [[On the Issues|OnTheIssues.org]], and is \"hard at work modernizing its extensive archives\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.snopes.com/ontheissues-coming-soon/ |title=Snopes Acquires On The Issues |website=Snopes |access-date=April 13, 2019}}</ref> OnTheIssues is a website that seeks to \"present all the relevant evidence, assess how strongly each piece supports or opposes a position, and summarize it with an average\" in order to \"provide voters with reliable information on candidates\u2019 policy positions\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://washingtonmonthly.com/2016/11/04/why-its-so-hard-to-find-out-where-the-candidates-stand/ |title=Why It\u2019s So Hard to Find Out Where the Candidates Stand |last=Potash |first=Eric |date=November 4, 2016 |website=Washington Monthly |access-date=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Main site==\nSnopes aims to debunk or confirm widely spread urban legends. The site has been referenced by news media and other sites, including [[CNN]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Nissen |first=Beth |url=http://www.cnn.com/2001/US/10/03/rec.false.rumors/index.html |title=Hear the rumor? Nostradamus and other tall tales |website=[[CNN]] |date=October 3, 2001 |access-date=June 7, 2009}}</ref>  [[MSNBC]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/17798063/ |title=Urban Legends Banned-April Fools'! |website=[[MSNBC]] |date=April 1, 2007 |access-date=June 7, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', and ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/politics/obama/muslim.asp |title=Urban Legends Reference Pages: Who Is Barack Obama? |date=August 24, 2008 |website=Snopes |access-date=January 22, 2008}}</ref> By March 2009, the site had more than 6 million visitors per month.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hochman |first=David |url=http://www.rd.com/your-america-inspiring-people-and-stories/rumor-detectives-true-story-or-online-hoax/article122216.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318123647/http://www.rd.com/your-america-inspiring-people-and-stories/rumor-detectives-true-story-or-online-hoax/article122216.html |archive-date=March 18, 2009 |date=March 2009 |website=[[Reader's Digest]] |title=Rumor Detectives: True Story or Online Hoax? |access-date=March 29, 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Mikkelson runs the website out of his home in [[Tacoma, Washington]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lacitis |first=Erik |date=October 10, 2018 |title=Lies, lies and more lies. Out of an old Tacoma house, fact-checking site Snopes uncovers them |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/lies-lies-and-more-lies-out-of-an-old-tacoma-house-fact-checking-site-snopes-uncovers-them/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |access-date=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMikkelson has stressed the ''reference'' portion of the name ''Urban Legends Reference Pages'', indicating that their intention is not merely to dismiss or confirm misconceptions and rumors but to provide evidence for such debunkings and confirmation as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/info/faq.asp |title=Urban Legends Reference Pages: Frequently Asked Questions |website=Snopes |quote=How do I know the information you've presented is accurate? |access-date=June 9, 2006}}</ref> Where appropriate, pages are generally marked \"undetermined\" or \"unverifiable\" when there is not enough evidence to either support or disprove a given claim.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/crime/warnings/roundrock.asp |title=Urban Legends Reference Pages: Round Rock Gangs |date=July 21, 2011 |website=Snopes |access-date=May 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Lost legends==\nIn an attempt to demonstrate the perils of over-reliance on the Internet as authority, Snopes assembled a series of fabricated urban folklore tales that it terms \"The Repository of Lost Legends\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/lost/lost.htm |title=Urban Legends Reference Pages: Lost Legends |website=Snopes |access-date=June 9, 2006}}</ref> The name was chosen for its acronym, T.R.O.L.L., a reference to the early 1990s definition of the word ''[[Internet troll|troll]]'', meaning an Internet prank or an Internet persona intended to be deliberately provocative or incendiary.<ref name=Porter />\n\n==Accuracy==\n[[Jan Harold Brunvand]], a [[folklorist]] who has written a number of books on urban legends and modern folklore, considered the site so comprehensive that in 2004 he decided not to launch one of his own to similarly discuss the accuracy of various legends and rumors.<ref name=\"Seipp\" />\n\nIn 2009, [[FactCheck.org]] reviewed a sample of Snopes' responses to political rumors regarding [[George W. Bush]], [[Sarah Palin]], and [[Barack Obama]], and found them to be free from bias in all cases.<ref name=\"FactCheck\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2235277/data-center/fact-checking-the-fact-checkers--snopes-com-gets-an--a-.html |title=Fact-checking the fact-checkers: Snopes.com gets an 'A' |website=[[Network World]] |date=April 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140707092627/https://www.networkworld.com/article/2235277/data-center/fact-checking-the-fact-checkers--snopes-com-gets-an--a-.html | archive-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> In 2012, ''[[The Florida Times-Union]]'' reported that [[About.com]]'s urban legends researcher found a \"consistent effort to provide even-handed analyses\" and that Snopes' cited sources and numerous reputable analyses of its content confirm its accuracy.<ref>{{cite news |first=Carole |last=Fader |title=Fact Check: So who's checking the fact-finders? We are |url=http://jacksonville.com/news/metro/2012-09-28/story/fact-check-so-whos-checking-fact-finders-we-are |work=[[The Florida Times-Union]] |date=September 28, 2012 |access-date=July 20, 2016}}</ref> Mikkelson has said that the site receives more complaints of liberal bias than conservative bias, but added that the same debunking standards are applied to all political urban legends.<ref name=\"FactCheck\">{{cite web |url=http://www.factcheck.org/2009/04/snopescom/ |title=Ask FactCheck: Snopes.com |website=[[FactCheck.org]] |date=April 10, 2009 |access-date=November 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Funding ==\nIn 2016, Snopes said that the entirety of its revenue was derived from advertising.<ref name=\"NYT\" />  However, in 2016, it also received an award of $75,000 from the [[James Randi Educational Foundation]], an organization formed to debunk paranormal claims. In 2017, it raised approximately $700,000 from a crowd-sourced GoFundMe effort and received $100,000 from Facebook as a part of a fact-checking partnership.<ref>{{cite web |title=Disclosures |url=https://www.snopes.com/disclosures/ |website=Snopes.com |access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 1, 2019, Snopes announced that it had ended its fact-checking partnership with Facebook. Snopes did not rule out the possibility of working with Facebook in the future but said it needed to \"determine with certainty that our efforts to aid any particular platform are a net positive for our online community, publication and staff\". Snopes added that the loss of revenue from the partnership meant the company would \"have less money to invest in our publication \u2014 and we will need to adapt to make up for it\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Green |first1=Vinny |last2=Mikkelson |first2=David |title=A Message to Our Community Regarding the Facebook Fact-Checking Partnership |url=https://www.snopes.com/snopes-fb-partnership-ends/ |website=Snopes.com |accessdate=2 February 2019 |date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Traffic and users==\nAs of December 2017, Snopes.com's Web traffic rank in the world stood at 3,798, with approximately 72% originating from the U.S. with web traffic declining from previous months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.similarweb.com/website/snopes.com|title=snopes.com Traffic Statistics|website=SimilarWeb|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2018}}</ref> {{as of|April 2017}}, Snopes.com's [[Alexa Internet|Alexa rating]] was 1,794. Approximately 80% of its visitors originate from within the [[United States]]. In 2017, the site attracted 20 million unique visitors in one month.<ref name=\"Stelter_Brian\">{{cite news |last=Stelter |first=Brian |title=Debunkers of Fictions Sift the Net |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/05/technology/05snopes.html |access-date=March 19, 2013 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 4, 2010 |url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.quantcast.com/snopes.com?country=US|title=Snopes.com Audience Insights |website=Quantcast |url-access=registration <!-- Do we need this restricted-access citation? -->}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Internet}}\n* {{annotated link|FactCheck.org}}\n* {{annotated link|List of common misconceptions}}\n* {{annotated link|MythBusters|''Mythbusters''}}\n* {{annotated link|The Straight Dope|''The Straight Dope''}}\n* {{annotated link|TruthOrFiction.com}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Urban Legends}}\n\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1995]]\n[[Category:Webby Award winners]]\n[[Category:Skepticism]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Fact-checking websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the novels by William Faulkner|Snopes trilogy}}\n{{short description|Fact-checking website}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = Snopes.com\n| logo             = Snopes logo.png\n| logo_size        = 150px\n| logo_alt         = Snopes logo\n| screenshot       = File:Snopes home page screenshot.png\n| url              = {{URL|https://www.snopes.com}}\n| commercial       = Yes\n| type             = Reference pages\n| registration     = Required only on forums\n| owner            = {{Plainlist|\n*David P. Mikkelson<ref name=webby>{{cite web |url=http://webbyawards.com/lists/how-the-truth-set-snopes-free |website=[[Webby Awards]] | title=How the Truth Set Snopes Free |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n*Proper Media<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|last1=Streitfeld|first1=David|title=For Fact Checking Website Snopes, a Bigger Role Brings More Attacks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/25/technology/for-fact-checking-website-snopes-a-bigger-role-brings-more-attacks.html?_r=0|access-date=December 27, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=December 25, 2016 |url-access=limited}}</ref>\n}}\n| author           = Barbara Mikkelson<br>David P. Mikkelson<ref name=webby />\n| launch_date      = 1994 (as Urban Legends Reference Pages)\n| alexa            = {{IncreaseNegative}}  3,290 (US 693) ({{as of|2018|2|05|alt=February 2019}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/snopes.com|title= Snopes.com Site Info|website=[[Alexa Internet]]|access-date=February 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| current_status   = Active\n}}\n\n'''Snopes''' ({{IPAc-en|s|n|o\u028a|p|s}}), formerly known as the '''Urban Legends Reference Pages''', is a [[Fact checking|fact-checking]] website.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4819108 |title=Snopes.com: Debunking Myths in Cyberspace] |website=[[NPR]] |date=August 27, 2005 |access-date=August 27, 2005}}</ref> It has been described as a \"well-regarded reference for sorting out myths and rumors\" on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/77880145/ |first=Melissa |last=Allison |title=Companies Find Rumors Hard to Kill on Internet |work=Herald and Review |date= March 4, 2007}} (image 3).</ref><ref>Same article: {{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/359621651 |title=Corporations Combat Insistent Urban Legends on Internet |work=The Courier |date=March 4, 2007}} (image 7).</ref> It has also been seen as a source for validating and [[Debunker|debunking]] [[urban legend]]s and similar stories in [[Culture of the United States|American popular culture]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Henry |first=Neil |title=American Carnival: Journalism Under Siege in an Age of New Media |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780520243422 |url-access=registration |publisher=University of California Press |year=2007 |p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780520243422/page/285 285]| quote=\"The most widely known resource for validating or debunking rumors, myths, hoaxes, and urban legends in popular American culture is the website run by Barbara and David P. Mikkelson at www.snopes.com...\"}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1994,<ref name=\"tri\">{{Cite web|url=https://twit.tv/shows/triangulation/episodes/343|title=Triangulation 343 David Mikkelson, Snopes.com |website=TWiT.tv|language=en-US|access-date=April 25, 2018}}</ref> David and Barbara Mikkelson created an urban [[folklore]] web site that would become Snopes.com. Snopes was an early [[online encyclopedia]] focused on urban legends, that mainly presented search results of user discussions. The site grew to encompass a wide range of subjects and became a resource to which Internet users began submitting pictures and stories of questionable veracity. According to the Mikkelsons, Snopes predated the [[search engine]] concept of fact-checking via search results.<ref name=\"nyt100405\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/05/technology/05snopes.html|title=Debunkers of Fictions Sift the Net|author=[[Brian Stelter]]|date=April 4, 2010|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 5, 2010 |url-access=limited}}</ref> David Mikkelson had originally adopted the username \"Snopes\" (the name of a family of often unpleasant people in the works of [[William Faulkner]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/info/faq.asp#snopes |title=Frequently Asked Questions |quote=What are 'snopes'? |website=Snopes |access-date=June 9, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Chron\">{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Bond |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |title=Web site separates fact from urban legend |url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Web-site-separates-fact-from-urban-legend-2800717.php |date=September 7, 2002 |access-date=July 17, 2012}}</ref> in the [[Usenet]] newsgroup alt.folklore.urban.<ref name=\"Chron\" /><ref name=\"Porter\">{{cite book |last=Porter |first=David |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KQLaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA48&lpg=PA48 |title=Internet Culture |chapter=Usenet Communities and the Cultural Politics of Information |publisher=[[Routledge]] |year=2013 |page=48 |isbn=978-1-135-20904-9 |access-date=September 13, 2016 |quote=The two most notorious trollers in AFU, [[Ted Frank]] and snopes, are also two of the most consistent posters of serious research.}}</ref><ref name=\"Seipp\">{{cite news |first=Cathy |last=Seipp |authorlink=Catherine Seipp |work=[[National Review]] |title=Where Urban Legends Fall |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/seipp/seipp200407210830.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040812075515/http://www.nationalreview.com/seipp/seipp200407210830.asp |archivedate=August 12, 2004 |access-date=February 7, 2014 |date=July 21, 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the site had become known well enough that a [[television pilot]] called ''Snopes: Urban Legends'' was completed with American actor [[Jim Davidson (actor)|Jim Davidson]] as host. However, it did not air on major networks.<ref name=\"Chron\" />\n\nBy mid-2014, Barbara had not written for Snopes \"in several years\"<ref name=\"webby\" /> and David was forced to hire users from Snopes.com's message board to assist him in running the site. The Mikkelsons divorced around that time.<ref name=\"webby\" /><ref name=\"Madrigal_Atlantic\">{{cite news |last1=Madrigal |first1=Alexis C. |title=Snopes Faces an Ugly Legal Battle |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2017/07/the-ugly-dispute-threatening-snopes/534708/ |work=[[The Atlantic]]  |date=July 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Chris Richmond (entrepreneur)|Christopher Richmond]] and Drew Schoentrup became part owners in July of 2016 with the purchase of Barbara Mikkelson's share by the internet media management company Proper Media.<ref name=\"CNS_Bruno\">{{cite news |last1=Bruno |first1=Bianca |title=Fact-Checker Snopes' Owners Accused of Corporate Subterfuge |url=https://www.courthousenews.com/fact-checker-snopes-owners-accused-corporate-subterfuge/ |website=[[Courthouse News Service|Courthouse News]] |date=May 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, 2017, David Mikkelson terminated the brokering agreement with Proper Media, which is also the company that provides Snopes with [[web development]], [[Web hosting service|hosting]], and [[Web advertising|advertising]] support.<ref name=\"WaPoLegal2017\">{{cite news|last1=Farhi|first1=Paul|title=Is Snopes.com, the original Internet fact-checker, going out of business?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/is-snopescom-the-original-internet-fact-checker-going-out-of-business/2017/07/24/8a03d196-708d-11e7-8839-ec48ec4cae25_story.html|work=The Washington Post|date=July 24, 2017}}</ref> This prompted Proper Media to stop remitting advertising revenue and to file a lawsuit in May. In late June, Bardav\u2014the company founded by David and Barbara Mikkelson in 2003 to own and operate snopes.com\u2014started a [[GoFundMe]] campaign to raise money to continue operations.<ref name=\"NYTLegal2017\">{{cite news|last1=Victor|first1=Daniel|title=Snopes, in Heated Legal Battle, Asks Readers for Money to Survive |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/24/business/media/snopes-crowdfunding-proper-media.html |work=The New York Times |date=July 24, 2017 |url-access=limited}}</ref> They raised $500,000 in 24 hours.<ref>{{cite web |title=Snopes Meets $500K Crowdfunding Goal Amid Legal Battle |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-25/snopes-launches-online-fundraiser-amid-legal-battle |website=[[Bloomberg Businessweek|Bloomberg]] |date=July 25, 2017 |access-date=December 18, 2017 |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Later, in August, a judge ordered Proper Media to disburse advertising revenues to Bardav while the case was pending.<ref name=\"WiredSnopes\">{{cite news |last1=Dean |first1=Michelle |title=Snopes and the Search for Facts in a Post-Fact World |url=https://www.wired.com/story/snopes-and-the-search-for-facts-in-a-post-fact-world? |date=September 20, 2017 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2019, Snopes announced that it had acquired the website [[On the Issues|OnTheIssues.org]], and is \"hard at work modernizing its extensive archives\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.snopes.com/ontheissues-coming-soon/ |title=Snopes Acquires On The Issues |website=Snopes |access-date=April 13, 2019}}</ref> OnTheIssues is a website that seeks to \"present all the relevant evidence, assess how strongly each piece supports or opposes a position, and summarize it with an average\" in order to \"provide voters with reliable information on candidates\u2019 policy positions\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://washingtonmonthly.com/2016/11/04/why-its-so-hard-to-find-out-where-the-candidates-stand/ |title=Why It\u2019s So Hard to Find Out Where the Candidates Stand |last=Potash |first=Eric |date=November 4, 2016 |website=Washington Monthly |access-date=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Main site==\nSnopes aims to debunk or confirm widely spread urban legends. The site has been referenced by news media and other sites, including [[CNN]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Nissen |first=Beth |url=http://www.cnn.com/2001/US/10/03/rec.false.rumors/index.html |title=Hear the rumor? Nostradamus and other tall tales |website=[[CNN]] |date=October 3, 2001 |access-date=June 7, 2009}}</ref>  [[MSNBC]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/17798063/ |title=Urban Legends Banned-April Fools'! |website=[[MSNBC]] |date=April 1, 2007 |access-date=June 7, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'', ''[[Forbes]]'', and ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/politics/obama/muslim.asp |title=Urban Legends Reference Pages: Who Is Barack Obama? |date=August 24, 2008 |website=Snopes |access-date=January 22, 2008}}</ref> By March 2009, the site had more than 6 million visitors per month.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hochman |first=David |url=http://www.rd.com/your-america-inspiring-people-and-stories/rumor-detectives-true-story-or-online-hoax/article122216.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318123647/http://www.rd.com/your-america-inspiring-people-and-stories/rumor-detectives-true-story-or-online-hoax/article122216.html |archive-date=March 18, 2009 |date=March 2009 |website=[[Reader's Digest]] |title=Rumor Detectives: True Story or Online Hoax? |access-date=March 29, 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Mikkelson runs the website out of his home in [[Tacoma, Washington]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lacitis |first=Erik |date=October 10, 2018 |title=Lies, lies and more lies. Out of an old Tacoma house, fact-checking site Snopes uncovers them |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/lies-lies-and-more-lies-out-of-an-old-tacoma-house-fact-checking-site-snopes-uncovers-them/ |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |access-date=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMikkelson has stressed the ''reference'' portion of the name ''Urban Legends Reference Pages'', indicating that their intention is not merely to dismiss or confirm misconceptions and rumors but to provide evidence for such debunkings and confirmation as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/info/faq.asp |title=Urban Legends Reference Pages: Frequently Asked Questions |website=Snopes |quote=How do I know the information you've presented is accurate? |access-date=June 9, 2006}}</ref> Where appropriate, pages are generally marked \"undetermined\" or \"unverifiable\" when there is not enough evidence to either support or disprove a given claim.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/crime/warnings/roundrock.asp |title=Urban Legends Reference Pages: Round Rock Gangs |date=July 21, 2011 |website=Snopes |access-date=May 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Lost legends==\nIn an attempt to demonstrate the perils of over-reliance on the Internet as authority, Snopes assembled a series of fabricated urban folklore tales that it terms \"The Repository of Lost Legends\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/lost/lost.htm |title=Urban Legends Reference Pages: Lost Legends |website=Snopes |access-date=June 9, 2006}}</ref> The name was chosen for its acronym, T.R.O.L.L., a reference to the early 1990s definition of the word ''[[Internet troll|troll]]'', meaning an Internet prank or an Internet persona intended to be deliberately provocative or incendiary.<ref name=Porter />\n\n==Accuracy==\n[[Jan Harold Brunvand]], a [[folklorist]] who has written a number of books on urban legends and modern folklore, considered the site so comprehensive that in 2004 he decided not to launch one of his own to similarly discuss the accuracy of various legends and rumors.<ref name=\"Seipp\" />\n\nIn 2009, [[FactCheck.org]] reviewed a sample of Snopes' responses to political rumors regarding [[George W. Bush]], [[Sarah Palin]], and [[Barack Obama]], and found them to be free from bias in all cases.<ref name=\"FactCheck\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2235277/data-center/fact-checking-the-fact-checkers--snopes-com-gets-an--a-.html |title=Fact-checking the fact-checkers: Snopes.com gets an 'A' |website=[[Network World]] |date=April 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140707092627/https://www.networkworld.com/article/2235277/data-center/fact-checking-the-fact-checkers--snopes-com-gets-an--a-.html | archive-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> In 2012, ''[[The Florida Times-Union]]'' reported that [[About.com]]'s urban legends researcher found a \"consistent effort to provide even-handed analyses\" and that Snopes' cited sources and numerous reputable analyses of its content confirm its accuracy.<ref>{{cite news |first=Carole |last=Fader |title=Fact Check: So who's checking the fact-finders? We are |url=http://jacksonville.com/news/metro/2012-09-28/story/fact-check-so-whos-checking-fact-finders-we-are |work=[[The Florida Times-Union]] |date=September 28, 2012 |access-date=July 20, 2016}}</ref> Mikkelson has said that the site receives more complaints of liberal bias than conservative bias, but added that the same debunking standards are applied to all political urban legends.<ref name=\"FactCheck\">{{cite web |url=http://www.factcheck.org/2009/04/snopescom/ |title=Ask FactCheck: Snopes.com |website=[[FactCheck.org]] |date=April 10, 2009 |access-date=November 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Funding ==\nIn 2016, Snopes said that the entirety of its revenue was derived from advertising.<ref name=\"NYT\" />  However, in 2016, it also received an award of $75,000 from the [[James Randi Educational Foundation]], an organization formed to debunk paranormal claims. In 2017, it raised approximately $700,000 from a crowd-sourced GoFundMe effort and received $100,000 from Facebook as a part of a fact-checking partnership.<ref>{{cite web |title=Disclosures |url=https://www.snopes.com/disclosures/ |website=Snopes.com |access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 1, 2019, Snopes announced that it had ended its fact-checking partnership with Facebook. Snopes did not rule out the possibility of working with Facebook in the future but said it needed to \"determine with certainty that our efforts to aid any particular platform are a net positive for our online community, publication and staff\". Snopes added that the loss of revenue from the partnership meant the company would \"have less money to invest in our publication \u2014 and we will need to adapt to make up for it\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Green |first1=Vinny |last2=Mikkelson |first2=David |title=A Message to Our Community Regarding the Facebook Fact-Checking Partnership |url=https://www.snopes.com/snopes-fb-partnership-ends/ |website=Snopes.com |accessdate=2 February 2019 |date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Traffic and users==\nAs of December 2017, Snopes.com's Web traffic rank in the world stood at 3,798, with approximately 72% originating from the U.S. with web traffic declining from previous months.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.similarweb.com/website/snopes.com|title=snopes.com Traffic Statistics|website=SimilarWeb|language=en|access-date=January 29, 2018}}</ref> {{as of|April 2017}}, Snopes.com's [[Alexa Internet|Alexa rating]] was 1,794. Approximately 80% of its visitors originate from within the [[United States]]. In 2017, the site attracted 20 million unique visitors in one month.<ref name=\"Stelter_Brian\">{{cite news |last=Stelter |first=Brian |title=Debunkers of Fictions Sift the Net |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/05/technology/05snopes.html |access-date=March 19, 2013 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 4, 2010 |url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.quantcast.com/snopes.com?country=US|title=Snopes.com Audience Insights |website=Quantcast |url-access=registration <!-- Do we need this restricted-access citation? -->}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Internet}}\n* {{annotated link|FactCheck.org}}\n* {{annotated link|List of common misconceptions}}\n* {{annotated link|MythBusters|''Mythbusters''}}\n* {{annotated link|The Straight Dope|''The Straight Dope''}}\n* {{annotated link|TruthOrFiction.com}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Urban Legends}}\n\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1995]]\n[[Category:Webby Award winners]]\n[[Category:Skepticism]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Fact-checking websites]]\n", "name_user": "Kwamikagami", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snopes"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Inch", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{short description|English strongman}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Thomas Inch\n| image      = Thomas Inch 1921.png\n|birth_date  = 27 December 1881 \n|birth_place = [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]]\n|death_date  = 12 December 1963\n|death_place = \n| occupation = Strongman}}{{Refimprove|date=April 2020}}'''Thomas Inch''' (27 December 1881 in [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[England]] &ndash; 12 December 1963) was a British strongman, holding the titles of Britain's Strongest Youth and [[Britain's Strongest Man]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bodybuilding.com/fun/ironhistory1.htm|title=INCH 101: An Introduction To The Basics.|date=12 December 2006|website=Bodybuilding.com|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916051811/http://www.bodybuilding.com/fun/ironhistory1.htm|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nThomas Inch was born on December 17, 1881 in Scarborough, a seaside town on the North Yorkshire coast. He became interested in [[bodybuilding]] and strength as a young boy, bodybuilding through [[manual labour]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Inch|first=Thomas|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ug-7MQEACAAJ&dq=thomas+inch&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjU0M6UqPnoAhXSbsAKHaWWBuIQ6AEIKDAA|title=Developing the Grip and Forearm|date=2012-04-08|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=978-1-4751-2710-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Lifting career ==\nIn 1902, aged 19, Inch was declared by a major '[[strongman]]' publication as the \u2018World\u2019s Strongest Youth, enhancing his notoriety. His inspirations included [[Eugen Sandow]], having seen the [[German]] ripping a [[Playing card|pack of cards]] in half and throwing the split deck into the audience. Inch was said to have caught one half of the pack, proceeded to split that in half in the audience, and throw is back at Sandow.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Klein|first=Alan M.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=z-ax2426Kw0C&pg=PA36&dq=thomas+inch&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjU0M6UqPnoAhXSbsAKHaWWBuIQ6AEINzAC|title=Little Big Men: Bodybuilding Subculture and Gender Construction|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-1-4384-0925-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\nUnlike many profesional [[Strongman|strongmen]] of his day, Inch focused on standard lifts with [[Barbell|barbells]] and [[Dumbbell|dumbbells]] and left the hoisting of [[Barrel|wooden barrels]], heavy sacks of grain, pianos, or holding back a team of horses, to his contemporaries. His one exception was that he sometimes lifted human beings in the bent-press; a complicated, one-hand movement to watch.\n\n=== Book & Capitalisation on fame ===\nInch realized in order to advance his fame and fortune as a world class strongman he needed to meet the prerequisite of publishing a well-written book pertaining to physical fitness. This, he accomplished in 1907, by authoring \"Thomas Inch on Strength.\" The following years, he traveled the British countryside performing exhibitions, selling his book, and spreading the Inch name.\n\n=== Britain's Strongest Man & World Records. ===\nInch went on to win the title of [[Britain's Strongest Man|Britain\u2019s Strongest Man]] on June 11, 1910. At the age of 68, Inch was still capable of [[Deadlift|deadlifting]] 540 pounds - an unofficial world record. His record lifts included a [[Two Hands Anyhow|two hands anyhow]] of 356 1/2 pounds and a [[bent press]] of 304 1/2 pounds.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Inch|first=Thomas|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ug-7MQEACAAJ&dq=thomas+inch&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjU0M6UqPnoAhXSbsAKHaWWBuIQ6AEIKDAA|title=Developing the Grip and Forearm|date=2012-04-08|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=978-1-4751-2710-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== The 'Thomas Inch' dumbbell ==\nHe is known for the Thomas Inch dumbbell, known as \"172\", a dumbbell that weighs 172&nbsp;lbs and 9 ounces(78.27kg). It was extremely difficult to lift, partly due to its weight, but primarily because its handle was very thick (2 3/8 inches(6cm) in diameter) making it difficult to hold on to without an outstandingly strong grip. There were allegations that there was a hole in the original 'bell, in which Thomas would place a nail, allowing him to arrest any rotation whilst lifting it. On 22 June 2002 Olympic Weightlifter and champion powerlifter [[Mark Henry]] completed a successful one-hand [[clean and jerk]] of the dumbbell.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H0lvfvxckxU |title=Archived copy |access-date=25 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116093123/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H0lvfvxckxU |archive-date=16 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nInch claimed that in his lifetime he never encountered anyone who could lift the 172 from the floor to overhead using only one hand. Even further he claimed that no one could clear it off the floor. He said he had overheaded it literally 'hundreds of times' sometimes lifting it twice in the same performance.[https://www.oldtimestrongman.com/blog/tag/thomas-inch/]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Prowse|first=David|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PEa5BAAAQBAJ&pg=PT225&dq=thomas+inch&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjU0M6UqPnoAhXSbsAKHaWWBuIQ6AEIQDAD|title=Straight From The Force\u2019s Mouth: The Autobiography of Dave Prowse|date=2011-09-28|publisher=Andrews UK Limited|isbn=978-1-908382-05-4|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1909 Inch, still only a middleweight, refused to compete in a weightlifting match against the Austrian [[Strongman (strength athlete)|strongman]] [[Max Sick]] (Maxick), who had recently arrived in [[London]]. However, by 1910 Inch had become a heavyweight and so relinquished his [[middleweight]] title to [[Edward Aston]], and a competition was quickly arranged against Sick.<ref name=\"Maxalding\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.maxalding.co.uk/maxick/maxbiog.htm|title=Max Sick's biography on maxalding.co.uk|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820164736/http://www.maxalding.co.uk/maxick/maxbiog.htm|archive-date=20 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Later Media Portrayal ==\nPro Wrestler Justin Gamache portrayed Sir Thomas Inch in the silent feature film Silent Times. It is directed by Christopher Annino and Geoff Blachette and was released in Italy on 14 September 2018. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6058070/fullcredits|title=Silent Times (2018) - IMDb|accessdate=10 April 2020|via=www.imdb.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328200106/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6058070/fullcredits/|archive-date=28 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n==Selected publications==\n\n*''Inch on Fitness'' (1923)\n*''Away with Nerves'' (1946)\n*''Manual of Physical Training'' (1947)\n*''Boxing for Beginners, from Novice to Champion'' (1951)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inch, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:English strength athletes]]\n[[Category:People associated with physical culture]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Scarborough, North Yorkshire]]\n\n\n\n{{England-sport-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{short description|English strongman}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Thomas Inch\n| image      = Thomas Inch 1921.png\n|birth_date  = 27 December 1881 \n|birth_place = [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]]\n|death_date  = 12 December 1963\n|death_place = \n| occupation = Strongman}}\n\n'''Thomas Inch''' (27 December 1881 in [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[England]] &ndash; 12 December 1963) was a British strongman, holding the titles of Britain's Strongest Youth and [[Britain's Strongest Man]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bodybuilding.com/fun/ironhistory1.htm|title=INCH 101: An Introduction To The Basics.|date=12 December 2006|website=Bodybuilding.com|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916051811/http://www.bodybuilding.com/fun/ironhistory1.htm|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nThomas Inch was born on December 17, 1881 in Scarborough, a seaside town on the North Yorkshire coast. He became interested in [[bodybuilding]] and strength as a young boy, bodybuilding through [[manual labour]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Inch|first=Thomas|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ug-7MQEACAAJ&dq=thomas+inch&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjU0M6UqPnoAhXSbsAKHaWWBuIQ6AEIKDAA|title=Developing the Grip and Forearm|date=2012-04-08|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=978-1-4751-2710-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Lifting career ==\nIn 1902, aged 19, Inch was declared by a major '[[strongman]]' publication as the \u2018World\u2019s Strongest Youth, enhancing his notoriety. His inspirations included [[Eugen Sandow]], having seen the [[German]] ripping a [[Playing card|pack of cards]] in half and throwing the split deck into the audience. Inch was said to have caught one half of the pack, proceeded to split that in half in the audience, and throw is back at Sandow.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Klein|first=Alan M.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=z-ax2426Kw0C&pg=PA36&dq=thomas+inch&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjU0M6UqPnoAhXSbsAKHaWWBuIQ6AEINzAC|title=Little Big Men: Bodybuilding Subculture and Gender Construction|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-1-4384-0925-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\nUnlike many profesional [[Strongman|strongmen]] of his day, Inch focused on standard lifts with [[Barbell|barbells]] and [[Dumbbell|dumbbells]] and left the hoisting of [[Barrel|wooden barrels]], heavy sacks of grain, pianos, or holding back a team of horses, to his contemporaries. His one exception was that he sometimes lifted human beings in the bent-press; a complicated, one-hand movement to watch.\n\n=== Book & Capitalisation on fame ===\nInch realized in order to advance his fame and fortune as a world class strongman he needed to meet the prerequisite of publishing a well-written book pertaining to physical fitness. This, he accomplished in 1907, by authoring \"Thomas Inch on Strength.\" The following years, he traveled the British countryside performing exhibitions, selling his book, and spreading the Inch name.\n\n=== Britain's Strongest Man & World Records. ===\nInch went on to win the title of [[Britain's Strongest Man|Britain\u2019s Strongest Man]] on June 11, 1910. At the age of 68, Inch was still capable of [[Deadlift|deadlifting]] 540 pounds - an unofficial world record. His record lifts included a [[Two Hands Anyhow|two hands anyhow]] of 356 1/2 pounds and a [[bent press]] of 304 1/2 pounds.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Inch|first=Thomas|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ug-7MQEACAAJ&dq=thomas+inch&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjU0M6UqPnoAhXSbsAKHaWWBuIQ6AEIKDAA|title=Developing the Grip and Forearm|date=2012-04-08|publisher=CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform|isbn=978-1-4751-2710-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== The 'Thomas Inch' dumbbell ==\nHe is known for the Thomas Inch dumbbell, known as \"172\", a dumbbell that weighs 172&nbsp;lbs and 9 ounces(78.27kg). It was extremely difficult to lift, partly due to its weight, but primarily because its handle was very thick (2 3/8 inches(6cm) in diameter) making it difficult to hold on to without an outstandingly strong grip. There were allegations that there was a hole in the original 'bell, in which Thomas would place a nail, allowing him to arrest any rotation whilst lifting it. On 22 June 2002 Olympic Weightlifter and champion powerlifter [[Mark Henry]] completed a successful one-hand [[clean and jerk]] of the dumbbell.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H0lvfvxckxU |title=Archived copy |access-date=25 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116093123/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H0lvfvxckxU |archive-date=16 January 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nInch claimed that in his lifetime he never encountered anyone who could lift the 172 from the floor to overhead using only one hand. Even further he claimed that no one could clear it off the floor. He said he had overheaded it literally 'hundreds of times' sometimes lifting it twice in the same performance.[https://www.oldtimestrongman.com/blog/tag/thomas-inch/]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Prowse|first=David|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PEa5BAAAQBAJ&pg=PT225&dq=thomas+inch&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjU0M6UqPnoAhXSbsAKHaWWBuIQ6AEIQDAD|title=Straight From The Force\u2019s Mouth: The Autobiography of Dave Prowse|date=2011-09-28|publisher=Andrews UK Limited|isbn=978-1-908382-05-4|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1909 Inch, still only a middleweight, refused to compete in a weightlifting match against the Austrian [[Strongman (strength athlete)|strongman]] [[Max Sick]] (Maxick), who had recently arrived in [[London]]. However, by 1910 Inch had become a heavyweight and so relinquished his [[middleweight]] title to [[Edward Aston]], and a competition was quickly arranged against Sick.<ref name=\"Maxalding\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.maxalding.co.uk/maxick/maxbiog.htm|title=Max Sick's biography on maxalding.co.uk|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820164736/http://www.maxalding.co.uk/maxick/maxbiog.htm|archive-date=20 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Later Media Portrayal ==\nPro Wrestler Justin Gamache portrayed Sir Thomas Inch in the silent feature film Silent Times. It is directed by Christopher Annino and Geoff Blachette and was released in Italy on 14 September 2018. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6058070/fullcredits|title=Silent Times (2018) - IMDb|accessdate=10 April 2020|via=www.imdb.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328200106/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6058070/fullcredits/|archive-date=28 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n==Selected publications==\n\n*''Inch on Fitness'' (1923)\n*''Away with Nerves'' (1946)\n*''Manual of Physical Training'' (1947)\n*''Boxing for Beginners, from Novice to Champion'' (1951)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inch, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:English strength athletes]]\n[[Category:People associated with physical culture]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Scarborough, North Yorkshire]]\n\n\n\n{{England-sport-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SerAntoniDeMiloni", "label": "safe", "comment": "More citations needed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Inch"}
{"title_page": "Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE \"Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke\" TO \"Bernd H\u00f6cke\". ATTEMPTS TO CHANGE THIS WILL BE UNDONE. THANK YOU. -->\n{{multiple issues|\n{{unreliable sources|date=October 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2015}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke<!---THIS NAME SHOULD NOT BE CHANGED WITHOUT CONSENSUS. FOR ANY RESERVATION ABOUT IT POST IT AT TALK PAGE-->\n| image         = 2019-10-27 Wahlabend Th\u00fcringen by Sandro Halank\u201388.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = H\u00f6cke in 2019\n| office        = Leader of [[Alternative for Germany]] in [[Thuringia]]\n| term_start    = February 2013\n| term_end      =\n| predecessor   = ''Office established''\n| successor     =\n| office2       = Member of the [[Landtag of Thuringia]]\n| term_start2   = 5 December 2014\n| term_end2     =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1972|04|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[L\u00fcnen]], [[Westphalia]], [[West Germany]]\n| party         = [[Alternative for Germany|AfD]] (2013\u2013present)\n| nationality   = German\n}}\n'''Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke'''<!---THIS NAME SHOULD NOT BE CHANGED WITHOUT CONSENSUS. FOR ANY RESERVATION ABOUT IT POST IT AT TALK PAGE--> (born 1 April 1972) is a  German politician and a member of [[Alternative for Germany]] (AfD). Along with Andreas Kalbitz, H\u00f6cke is the leader of the AfD's [[far-right]] \"[[Der Fl\u00fcgel]]\" faction, which the German government's [[Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution]] declared a [[right-wing extremist]] organization.<ref name=Schuetze>Christopher F. Schuetze, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/world/europe/germany-populist-party.html Far-Right Faction of German Populist Party Vows to Dissolve], ''New York Times'' (March 25, 2020).</ref><ref name=Bennhold>Katrin Bennhold, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/world/europe/germany-afd.html Germany Places Part of Far-Right Party Under Surveillance], ''New York Times'' (March 12, 2020).</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke was born in [[L\u00fcnen]], [[Westphalia]]. His grandparents were [[Heimatvertriebene|expelled ethnic Germans]] from [[East Prussia]]. He took his [[Abitur]] at the Rhein-Wied-Gymnasium Neuwied in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.der-lokalanzeiger.de/index.php/articles/8996/fraktionsvorsitzender-der-af-d-bj|work=Der Lokalanzeiger|title=Fraktionsvorsitzender der AfD Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke besucht seine Heimatstadt Neuwied|date=24 April 2015|access-date=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131064044/http://www.der-lokalanzeiger.de/index.php/articles/8996/fraktionsvorsitzender-der-af-d-bj|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nH\u00f6cke is a former history teacher,<ref name=Bennhold/> teaching at the Rhenanus School, a comprehensive school in [[Bad Sooden-Allendorf]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fr.de/rhein-main/rechtsextremismus-sti84176/bjoern-hoecke-afd-politiker-fluegel-bleibt-beamter-hessen-13553978.html|title=Trotz \u201emenschenfeindlicher Positionen\u201c: AfD-Politiker Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke bleibt Beamter in Hessen|last=|first=|date=2020-02-25|website=Frankfurter Allgemeine|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> \n\n==Political career==\nH\u00f6cke was a short-time member of the [[Young Union|Junge Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article148318308/AfD-Rechtsaussen-Hoecke-ist-von-ganz-alter-Schule.html|title=AfD-Rechtsau\u00dfen H\u00f6cke ist von ganz alter Schule|work=[[Die Welt]]|date=2 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs one of the founders of AfD Thuringia, he became Member of the [[Landtag of Thuringia]], the state assembly of the federal state of [[Thuringia]] in Germany during the [[2014 Thuringian state election|2014 Thuringian State Elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tlz.de/web/zgt/suche/detail/-/specific/Landtagswahl-2014-Welche-Koalitionen-sind-in-Thueringen-moeglich-179394471|title=Landtagswahl 2014: Welche Koalitionen sind in Th\u00fcringen m\u00f6glich?\"|work=[[Th\u00fcringische Landeszeitung]]|date=16 July 2014}}</ref> H\u00f6cke is the speaker of the parliamentary group of the AfD and he is the spokesman of the Thuringia Landesverband (English: Regional Association) of his party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afd-thueringen.de/vorstand/|title=AfD Vorstand Th\u00fcringen}}</ref>  He is said to be part of the [[national-conservative|\u201cnational-conservative wing\u201d]] of the AfD.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/thueringen-immunitaet-von-afd-fraktionschef-hoecke-aufgehoben-a-1042010.html|title= Th\u00fcringen: Ausschuss hebt Immunit\u00e4t von AfD-Fraktionschef H\u00f6cke auf|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=3 July 2015}}</ref> His faction of the party is known as the [[Der Fl\u00fcgel|Fl\u00fcgel]] (the Wing)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Huggler|first=Justin|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/27/germanys-new-hitler-poised-lead-afd-regional-election-gains/|title=Germany's 'new Hitler' poised to lead AfD to regional election gains|date=2019-10-27|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and 40 percent of the AfD party members identify themselves with it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/afds-bj%C3%B6rn-h%C3%B6cke-firebrand-of-the-german-far-right/a-52297134|title=AfD's Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke: Firebrand of the German far right|publisher=Deutsche Welle|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> \n\nIn September 2019, H\u00f6cke threatened \"massive consequences\" to a [[ZDF]] journalist who refused to restart an interview after a series of difficult questions and after asking fellow party members whether various quotes are from his book or from Hitler's ''[[Mein Kampf]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/sep/16/afd-politician-threatens-journalist-hitler-comparison-bjorn-hocke?CMP|title=AfD politician threatens journalist after Hitler comparison|last=|first=|date=|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Political views and controversies==\nH\u00f6cke espouses [[far-right]] views.<ref name=nytimes2017>{{cite web|author=Katrin Bennhold|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/25/world/europe/germany-bjorn-hocke-bornhagen.html|title=For One Far-Right Politician, Forgetting Germany's Past Just Got Harder|work=The New York Times|date=December 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref>  [[Political scientists]] such as Gero Neugebauer and Hajo Funke have commented that H\u00f6cke's opinions are close to the [[National Democratic Party of Germany]] and consider his statements [[v\u00f6lkisch]], [[racist]] and [[fascist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/politik/deutschland/thueringen-afd-chef-hoecke-eindeutig-rechtsextremistisch/12474498.html|title=Eindeutig rechtsextremistisch|work=[[Handelsblatt]]|date=2 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deutschlandfunk.de/politikwissenschaftler-funke-die-afd-hat-sich.694.de.html?dram:article_id=334837|title=Die AfD hat sich rechtsradikalisiert|work=[[Deutschlandfunk]]|date=23 October 2015}}</ref> In September 2019, a German court ruled that H\u00f6cke could legally be called a fascist as the description \"rests on verifiable fact\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olterman |first1=Philip |title=Outrage as German centre-right votes with AfD to oust Thuringia premier |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/05/centre-right-german-parties-vote-with-afd-to-oust-thuringia-premier-bodo-ramelow |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=5 February 2020 |date=5 February 2020}}</ref> He is reported to have declared that if Europe would keep on taking in immigrants, the African \"reproductive behavior\" will not change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/what-does-the-afd-stand-for/a-19100127|title=What does the AfD stand for?|last=Knight|first=Ben|date=July 3, 2016|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> Regarding the [[European migrant crisis]], H\u00f6cke opposes Germany's [[right of asylum|asylum]] policy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2014-08/afd-schengen-aussetzung|title=AfD fordert Aussetzung des Schengener Abkommens|work=[[Die Zeit]]|date=27 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article148369724/Welche-Rechten-stecken-hinter-dem-schwarzen-Haken.html|title=Welche Rechten stecken hinter dem schwarzen Haken?|newspaper=[[Die Welt]]|date=3 November 2015|last1=Leubecher|first1=Marcel}}</ref> leading regular demonstrations in Erfurt against the federal government's asylum policy, which regularly attracted several thousand sympathizers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/rechtspopulist-hessen-will-afd-politiker-hoecke-nicht-mehr-unterrichten-lassen/12839816.html|title=Hessen will AfD-Politiker H\u00f6cke nicht mehr unterrichten lassen |work=[[Der Tagesspiegel]]|date=18 January 2016}}</ref> He opposes the [[euro]], favoring a return to national currencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wen-waehlen.de/btw13/kandidaten/27120-bjoern-hoecke.html|title=Kandidaten Bundestagswahl 2013|work=[[wen-w\u00e4hlen.de]]|date=2013}}</ref>\n\nH\u00f6cke has called for more \"Prussian virtues\" and promotes [[Natalism|natalist]] views, specifically the \"three-child family as a political and social model.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tlz.de/politik/afd-kandidat-hoecke-im-interview-drei-kinder-familie-ist-politisches-leitbild-id220276337.html|title=AfD Kandidat H\u00f6cke im Interview: Drei-Kinder-Familie ist politisches Leitbild|date=21 July 2014|work=[[Th\u00fcringische Landeszeitung]]}}</ref> He opposes [[gender mainstreaming]] and demands an end of what he calls \"social experiments\" that undermine what he deems the \"natural gender order.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.taz.de/!5033115/|title=Nat\u00fcrliche Geschlechterordnung|work=[[Die Tageszeitung]]|date=17 September 2014|last1=Oestreich|first1=Heide}}</ref> He opposes the [[Mainstreaming (education)|mainstreaming]] of students with disabilities, calling for such students to go the separate schools, and opposes school [[sexual education]], which he regards as \"early sexualization of the students,\" and wants to \"stop the dissolution of the natural polarity of the two sexes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pnn.de/brandenburg-berlin/878388/|title=AfD will sich mit rechten Thesen profilieren|work=[[Der Tagesspiegel]]|date=31 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 email to party colleagues, H\u00f6cke advocated the abolition of [[Strafgesetzbuch section 86a|section 86]] of the [[Strafgesetzbuch|German Criminal Code]] (which prohibits the spread of propaganda by unconstitutional organizations) and section 130 of the German Criminal Code (which criminalizes [[Volksverhetzung|incitement to hatred towards other groups]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.focus.de/regional/erfurt/parteien-hoecke-sorgt-erneut-mit-aeusserungen-fuer-wirbel_id_4715382.html |title=H\u00f6cke sorgt erneut mit \u00c4u\u00dferungen f\u00fcr Wirbel |work=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]] |date=29 May 2015 |language=de }}</ref> This would also have legalized [[Holocaust denial]], which is [[Laws against Holocaust denial#Germany|illegal in Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mdr.de/thueringen/afd-hoecke-e-mail100.html |title=Neuer Beleg f\u00fcr NPD-N\u00e4he von AfD-Landeschef H\u00f6cke In: MDR.de vom 29. Mai 2015. |access-date=January 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530164111/http://www.mdr.de/thueringen/afd-hoecke-e-mail100.html |archive-date=May 30, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nH\u00f6cke has links with [[Neo-Nazism in Germany|neo-Nazi]] circles in Germany.<ref name=Schuetze/><ref name=Bennhold/> H\u00f6cke has written with Thorsten Heise, a leader of [[Nationaldemokratische Partei Deutschland|NPD]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u00bbKeiner traut sich an H\u00f6cke heran\u00ab|periodical=|publisher=|url=https://jungle.world/artikel/2019/12/keiner-traut-sich-hoecke-heran|url-status=|format=|access-date=2019-03-26|archive-url=|archive-date=|last=|date=|year=|language=de|pages=|quote=}}</ref><ref>Andreas Kemper: [https://www.freitag.de/autoren/der-freitag/im-dienste-einer-grossen-abrechnung ''Im Dienste einer gro\u00dfen \u201eAbrechnung\u201c''], in: ''der Freitag'', Ausg. 26/2019, abgerufen am 4. Juli 2019.</ref> In 2015 H\u00f6cke was accused of having contributed to Heise's journal ''People in Motion'' (''Volk in Bewegung'') and ''The Reichsbote'' under a pseudonym (\"Landolf Ladig\"). H\u00f6cke denied having ever written for NPD papers, but refused to give a [[statutory declaration]] as demanded by the AfD Federal Executive Board.<ref name=\"SPON-1031302\">Severin Weiland, Christina Hebel: [http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/afd-landeschef-hoecke-lehnt-erklaerung-zu-npd-ab-a-1031302.html ''Mutma\u00dflicher Kontakt zur NPD: AfD-Landeschef H\u00f6cke lehnt eidesstattliche Erkl\u00e4rung ab.''] Spiegel, 29. April 2015</ref><ref>Hannes Vogel: [https://www.zeit.de/2018/38/bjoern-hoecke-afd-neonazi-freundschaft-rechtsextremismus/komplettansicht ''Alte Kameraden.''] Zeit, 13. September 2018</ref>\n\n===Allegations of antisemitism===\n[[File:Bornhagen Friedensstr Nachbildung Holocaust-Mahnmal 1 2018-01-01.jpg|thumb|right|A replica of the Holocaust memorial was erected on the property adjacent to H\u00f6cke.]]\nH\u00f6cke gave a speech in Dresden in January 2017, in which, referring to the Holocaust memorial in Berlin (the [[Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe]]), he stated that \"we Germans are the only people in the world who have planted a memorial of shame in the heart of their capital\"<ref name=\"FAZ-2017\">{{cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/inland/afd-geht-nach-umstrittener-rede-auf-distanz-zu-hoecke-14686499.html|title=AfD-Mann H\u00f6cke l\u00f6st mit Kritik an Holocaust-Gedenken Emp\u00f6rung aus|work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]|date=January 18, 2017|language=de}}</ref> and suggested that Germans \"need to make a 180 degree change in their commemoration policy\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article161286915/Was-Hoecke-mit-der-Denkmal-der-Schande-Rede-bezweckt.html|title=Was H\u00f6cke mit der \"Denkmal der Schande\"-Rede bezweckt|author=Matthias Kamann|newspaper=[[Die Welt]]|date=January 19, 2017|language=de}}</ref> The speech was widely criticized as [[Antisemitism|antisemitic]], among others by Jewish leaders in Germany, and he was described by his party chairwoman, [[Frauke Petry]], in response as a \u201cburden to the party\u201d.<ref name=\"FAZ-2017\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://jungefreiheit.de/politik/deutschland/2017/petry-hoecke-ist-eine-belastung-fuer-die-partei/|title=AfD-Chefin Petry: \"H\u00f6cke ist eine Belastung f\u00fcr die Partei\"|work=Junge Freiheit|date=January 18, 2017|language=de}}</ref> As a result of his speech, the majority of leaders of the AfD asked in February 2017 that Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke be expelled from the party. In May 2018 an AfD tribunal ruled that H\u00f6cke was allowed to stay in the party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/germanys-right-wing-afd-seeks-to-expel-state-leader-over-holocaust-remarks/a-37525199|title=Germany's right-wing AfD seeks to expel state leader over Holocaust remarks|first=|last=|publisher=Deutsche Welle}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> After H\u00f6cke's \"monument of shame\" comment, the Center for Political Beauty, a Berlin-based [[art collective]], erected a full-scale replica of one section of the Holocaust memorial in Berlin within viewing distance of H\u00f6cke's home in [[Bornhagen]] as a reminder of German history.<ref name=nytimes2017/>\n\nA video of H\u00f6cke emerged in March 2020 in which he used an [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] pun while attacking critics of his Fl\u00fcgel faction. The faction had been placed under surveillance by the [[Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution]] shortly before the video surfaced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/afd-bald-komplett-vom-verfassungsschutz-beobachtet-hoecke-schockiert-mit-auschwitz-wortspiel/25647770.html|title=H\u00f6cke schockiert mit Auschwitz-Wortspiel|website=www.tagesspiegel.de|language=de|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.bjoern-hoecke.de/ Official website]\n* [http://www.thueringer-landtag.de/landtag/abgeordnete-und-fraktionen/abgeordnete/biografien/daten/87163/index.aspx Official Th\u00fcringer Landtag profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hocke, Bjorn}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Alternative for Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Landtag of Thuringia]]\n[[Category:People from L\u00fcnen]]\n[[Category:21st-century German politicians]]\n[[Category:German fascists]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE \"Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke\" TO \"Bernd H\u00f6cke\". ATTEMPTS TO CHANGE THIS WILL BE UNDONE. THANK YOU. -->\n{{multiple issues|\n{{unreliable sources|date=October 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2015}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke<!---THIS NAME SHOULD NOT BE CHANGED WITHOUT CONSENSUS. FOR ANY RESERVATION ABOUT IT POST IT AT TALK PAGE-->\n| image         = 2019-10-27 Wahlabend Th\u00fcringen by Sandro Halank\u201388.jpg\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = H\u00f6cke in 2019\n| office        = Leader of [[Alternative for Germany]] in [[Thuringia]]\n| term_start    = February 2013\n| term_end      =\n| predecessor   = ''Office established''\n| successor     =\n| office2       = Member of the [[Landtag of Thuringia]]\n| term_start2   = 5 December 2014\n| term_end2     =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1972|04|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[L\u00fcnen]], [[Westphalia]], [[West Germany]]\n| party         = [[Alternative for Germany|AfD]] (2013\u2013present)\n| nationality   = German\n}}\n'''Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke'''<!---THIS NAME SHOULD NOT BE CHANGED WITHOUT CONSENSUS. FOR ANY RESERVATION ABOUT IT POST IT AT TALK PAGE--> (born 1 April 1972) is a [[Fascism|fascist]] German politician and a member of [[Alternative for Germany]] (AfD). Along with Andreas Kalbitz, H\u00f6cke is the leader of the AfD's [[far-right]] \"[[Der Fl\u00fcgel]]\" faction, which the German government's [[Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution]] declared a [[right-wing extremist]] organization.<ref name=Schuetze>Christopher F. Schuetze, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/world/europe/germany-populist-party.html Far-Right Faction of German Populist Party Vows to Dissolve], ''New York Times'' (March 25, 2020).</ref><ref name=Bennhold>Katrin Bennhold, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/world/europe/germany-afd.html Germany Places Part of Far-Right Party Under Surveillance], ''New York Times'' (March 12, 2020).</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke was born in [[L\u00fcnen]], [[Westphalia]]. His grandparents were [[Heimatvertriebene|expelled ethnic Germans]] from [[East Prussia]]. He took his [[Abitur]] at the Rhein-Wied-Gymnasium Neuwied in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.der-lokalanzeiger.de/index.php/articles/8996/fraktionsvorsitzender-der-af-d-bj|work=Der Lokalanzeiger|title=Fraktionsvorsitzender der AfD Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke besucht seine Heimatstadt Neuwied|date=24 April 2015|access-date=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131064044/http://www.der-lokalanzeiger.de/index.php/articles/8996/fraktionsvorsitzender-der-af-d-bj|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nH\u00f6cke is a former history teacher,<ref name=Bennhold/> teaching at the Rhenanus School, a comprehensive school in [[Bad Sooden-Allendorf]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fr.de/rhein-main/rechtsextremismus-sti84176/bjoern-hoecke-afd-politiker-fluegel-bleibt-beamter-hessen-13553978.html|title=Trotz \u201emenschenfeindlicher Positionen\u201c: AfD-Politiker Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke bleibt Beamter in Hessen|last=|first=|date=2020-02-25|website=Frankfurter Allgemeine|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> \n\n==Political career==\nH\u00f6cke was a short-time member of the [[Young Union|Junge Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article148318308/AfD-Rechtsaussen-Hoecke-ist-von-ganz-alter-Schule.html|title=AfD-Rechtsau\u00dfen H\u00f6cke ist von ganz alter Schule|work=[[Die Welt]]|date=2 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs one of the founders of AfD Thuringia, he became Member of the [[Landtag of Thuringia]], the state assembly of the federal state of [[Thuringia]] in Germany during the [[2014 Thuringian state election|2014 Thuringian State Elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tlz.de/web/zgt/suche/detail/-/specific/Landtagswahl-2014-Welche-Koalitionen-sind-in-Thueringen-moeglich-179394471|title=Landtagswahl 2014: Welche Koalitionen sind in Th\u00fcringen m\u00f6glich?\"|work=[[Th\u00fcringische Landeszeitung]]|date=16 July 2014}}</ref> H\u00f6cke is the speaker of the parliamentary group of the AfD and he is the spokesman of the Thuringia Landesverband (English: Regional Association) of his party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afd-thueringen.de/vorstand/|title=AfD Vorstand Th\u00fcringen}}</ref>  He is said to be part of the [[national-conservative|\u201cnational-conservative wing\u201d]] of the AfD.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/thueringen-immunitaet-von-afd-fraktionschef-hoecke-aufgehoben-a-1042010.html|title= Th\u00fcringen: Ausschuss hebt Immunit\u00e4t von AfD-Fraktionschef H\u00f6cke auf|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|date=3 July 2015}}</ref> His faction of the party is known as the [[Der Fl\u00fcgel|Fl\u00fcgel]] (the Wing)<ref>{{Cite news|last=Huggler|first=Justin|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/27/germanys-new-hitler-poised-lead-afd-regional-election-gains/|title=Germany's 'new Hitler' poised to lead AfD to regional election gains|date=2019-10-27|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> and 40 percent of the AfD party members identify themselves with it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/afds-bj%C3%B6rn-h%C3%B6cke-firebrand-of-the-german-far-right/a-52297134|title=AfD's Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke: Firebrand of the German far right|publisher=Deutsche Welle|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> \n\nIn September 2019, H\u00f6cke threatened \"massive consequences\" to a [[ZDF]] journalist who refused to restart an interview after a series of difficult questions and after asking fellow party members whether various quotes are from his book or from Hitler's ''[[Mein Kampf]]''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/sep/16/afd-politician-threatens-journalist-hitler-comparison-bjorn-hocke?CMP|title=AfD politician threatens journalist after Hitler comparison|last=|first=|date=|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Political views and controversies==\nH\u00f6cke espouses [[far-right]] views.<ref name=nytimes2017>{{cite web|author=Katrin Bennhold|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/25/world/europe/germany-bjorn-hocke-bornhagen.html|title=For One Far-Right Politician, Forgetting Germany's Past Just Got Harder|work=The New York Times|date=December 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref>  [[Political scientists]] such as Gero Neugebauer and Hajo Funke have commented that H\u00f6cke's opinions are close to the [[National Democratic Party of Germany]] and consider his statements [[v\u00f6lkisch]], [[racist]] and [[fascist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/politik/deutschland/thueringen-afd-chef-hoecke-eindeutig-rechtsextremistisch/12474498.html|title=Eindeutig rechtsextremistisch|work=[[Handelsblatt]]|date=2 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deutschlandfunk.de/politikwissenschaftler-funke-die-afd-hat-sich.694.de.html?dram:article_id=334837|title=Die AfD hat sich rechtsradikalisiert|work=[[Deutschlandfunk]]|date=23 October 2015}}</ref> In September 2019, a German court ruled that H\u00f6cke could legally be called a fascist as the description \"rests on verifiable fact\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olterman |first1=Philip |title=Outrage as German centre-right votes with AfD to oust Thuringia premier |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/05/centre-right-german-parties-vote-with-afd-to-oust-thuringia-premier-bodo-ramelow |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=5 February 2020 |date=5 February 2020}}</ref> He is reported to have declared that if Europe would keep on taking in immigrants, the African \"reproductive behavior\" will not change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/what-does-the-afd-stand-for/a-19100127|title=What does the AfD stand for?|last=Knight|first=Ben|date=July 3, 2016|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> Regarding the [[European migrant crisis]], H\u00f6cke opposes Germany's [[right of asylum|asylum]] policy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2014-08/afd-schengen-aussetzung|title=AfD fordert Aussetzung des Schengener Abkommens|work=[[Die Zeit]]|date=27 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article148369724/Welche-Rechten-stecken-hinter-dem-schwarzen-Haken.html|title=Welche Rechten stecken hinter dem schwarzen Haken?|newspaper=[[Die Welt]]|date=3 November 2015|last1=Leubecher|first1=Marcel}}</ref> leading regular demonstrations in Erfurt against the federal government's asylum policy, which regularly attracted several thousand sympathizers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/rechtspopulist-hessen-will-afd-politiker-hoecke-nicht-mehr-unterrichten-lassen/12839816.html|title=Hessen will AfD-Politiker H\u00f6cke nicht mehr unterrichten lassen |work=[[Der Tagesspiegel]]|date=18 January 2016}}</ref> He opposes the [[euro]], favoring a return to national currencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wen-waehlen.de/btw13/kandidaten/27120-bjoern-hoecke.html|title=Kandidaten Bundestagswahl 2013|work=[[wen-w\u00e4hlen.de]]|date=2013}}</ref>\n\nH\u00f6cke has called for more \"Prussian virtues\" and promotes [[Natalism|natalist]] views, specifically the \"three-child family as a political and social model.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tlz.de/politik/afd-kandidat-hoecke-im-interview-drei-kinder-familie-ist-politisches-leitbild-id220276337.html|title=AfD Kandidat H\u00f6cke im Interview: Drei-Kinder-Familie ist politisches Leitbild|date=21 July 2014|work=[[Th\u00fcringische Landeszeitung]]}}</ref> He opposes [[gender mainstreaming]] and demands an end of what he calls \"social experiments\" that undermine what he deems the \"natural gender order.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.taz.de/!5033115/|title=Nat\u00fcrliche Geschlechterordnung|work=[[Die Tageszeitung]]|date=17 September 2014|last1=Oestreich|first1=Heide}}</ref> He opposes the [[Mainstreaming (education)|mainstreaming]] of students with disabilities, calling for such students to go the separate schools, and opposes school [[sexual education]], which he regards as \"early sexualization of the students,\" and wants to \"stop the dissolution of the natural polarity of the two sexes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pnn.de/brandenburg-berlin/878388/|title=AfD will sich mit rechten Thesen profilieren|work=[[Der Tagesspiegel]]|date=31 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 email to party colleagues, H\u00f6cke advocated the abolition of [[Strafgesetzbuch section 86a|section 86]] of the [[Strafgesetzbuch|German Criminal Code]] (which prohibits the spread of propaganda by unconstitutional organizations) and section 130 of the German Criminal Code (which criminalizes [[Volksverhetzung|incitement to hatred towards other groups]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.focus.de/regional/erfurt/parteien-hoecke-sorgt-erneut-mit-aeusserungen-fuer-wirbel_id_4715382.html |title=H\u00f6cke sorgt erneut mit \u00c4u\u00dferungen f\u00fcr Wirbel |work=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]] |date=29 May 2015 |language=de }}</ref> This would also have legalized [[Holocaust denial]], which is [[Laws against Holocaust denial#Germany|illegal in Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mdr.de/thueringen/afd-hoecke-e-mail100.html |title=Neuer Beleg f\u00fcr NPD-N\u00e4he von AfD-Landeschef H\u00f6cke In: MDR.de vom 29. Mai 2015. |access-date=January 20, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530164111/http://www.mdr.de/thueringen/afd-hoecke-e-mail100.html |archive-date=May 30, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nH\u00f6cke has links with [[Neo-Nazism in Germany|neo-Nazi]] circles in Germany.<ref name=Schuetze/><ref name=Bennhold/> H\u00f6cke has written with Thorsten Heise, a leader of [[Nationaldemokratische Partei Deutschland|NPD]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u00bbKeiner traut sich an H\u00f6cke heran\u00ab|periodical=|publisher=|url=https://jungle.world/artikel/2019/12/keiner-traut-sich-hoecke-heran|url-status=|format=|access-date=2019-03-26|archive-url=|archive-date=|last=|date=|year=|language=de|pages=|quote=}}</ref><ref>Andreas Kemper: [https://www.freitag.de/autoren/der-freitag/im-dienste-einer-grossen-abrechnung ''Im Dienste einer gro\u00dfen \u201eAbrechnung\u201c''], in: ''der Freitag'', Ausg. 26/2019, abgerufen am 4. Juli 2019.</ref> In 2015 H\u00f6cke was accused of having contributed to Heise's journal ''People in Motion'' (''Volk in Bewegung'') and ''The Reichsbote'' under a pseudonym (\"Landolf Ladig\"). H\u00f6cke denied having ever written for NPD papers, but refused to give a [[statutory declaration]] as demanded by the AfD Federal Executive Board.<ref name=\"SPON-1031302\">Severin Weiland, Christina Hebel: [http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/afd-landeschef-hoecke-lehnt-erklaerung-zu-npd-ab-a-1031302.html ''Mutma\u00dflicher Kontakt zur NPD: AfD-Landeschef H\u00f6cke lehnt eidesstattliche Erkl\u00e4rung ab.''] Spiegel, 29. April 2015</ref><ref>Hannes Vogel: [https://www.zeit.de/2018/38/bjoern-hoecke-afd-neonazi-freundschaft-rechtsextremismus/komplettansicht ''Alte Kameraden.''] Zeit, 13. September 2018</ref>\n\n===Allegations of antisemitism===\n[[File:Bornhagen Friedensstr Nachbildung Holocaust-Mahnmal 1 2018-01-01.jpg|thumb|right|A replica of the Holocaust memorial was erected on the property adjacent to H\u00f6cke.]]\nH\u00f6cke gave a speech in Dresden in January 2017, in which, referring to the Holocaust memorial in Berlin (the [[Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe]]), he stated that \"we Germans are the only people in the world who have planted a memorial of shame in the heart of their capital\"<ref name=\"FAZ-2017\">{{cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/inland/afd-geht-nach-umstrittener-rede-auf-distanz-zu-hoecke-14686499.html|title=AfD-Mann H\u00f6cke l\u00f6st mit Kritik an Holocaust-Gedenken Emp\u00f6rung aus|work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]|date=January 18, 2017|language=de}}</ref> and suggested that Germans \"need to make a 180 degree change in their commemoration policy\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/deutschland/article161286915/Was-Hoecke-mit-der-Denkmal-der-Schande-Rede-bezweckt.html|title=Was H\u00f6cke mit der \"Denkmal der Schande\"-Rede bezweckt|author=Matthias Kamann|newspaper=[[Die Welt]]|date=January 19, 2017|language=de}}</ref> The speech was widely criticized as [[Antisemitism|antisemitic]], among others by Jewish leaders in Germany, and he was described by his party chairwoman, [[Frauke Petry]], in response as a \u201cburden to the party\u201d.<ref name=\"FAZ-2017\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://jungefreiheit.de/politik/deutschland/2017/petry-hoecke-ist-eine-belastung-fuer-die-partei/|title=AfD-Chefin Petry: \"H\u00f6cke ist eine Belastung f\u00fcr die Partei\"|work=Junge Freiheit|date=January 18, 2017|language=de}}</ref> As a result of his speech, the majority of leaders of the AfD asked in February 2017 that Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke be expelled from the party. In May 2018 an AfD tribunal ruled that H\u00f6cke was allowed to stay in the party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/germanys-right-wing-afd-seeks-to-expel-state-leader-over-holocaust-remarks/a-37525199|title=Germany's right-wing AfD seeks to expel state leader over Holocaust remarks|first=|last=|publisher=Deutsche Welle}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> After H\u00f6cke's \"monument of shame\" comment, the Center for Political Beauty, a Berlin-based [[art collective]], erected a full-scale replica of one section of the Holocaust memorial in Berlin within viewing distance of H\u00f6cke's home in [[Bornhagen]] as a reminder of German history.<ref name=nytimes2017/>\n\nA video of H\u00f6cke emerged in March 2020 in which he used an [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] pun while attacking critics of his Fl\u00fcgel faction. The faction had been placed under surveillance by the [[Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution]] shortly before the video surfaced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/afd-bald-komplett-vom-verfassungsschutz-beobachtet-hoecke-schockiert-mit-auschwitz-wortspiel/25647770.html|title=H\u00f6cke schockiert mit Auschwitz-Wortspiel|website=www.tagesspiegel.de|language=de|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.bjoern-hoecke.de/ Official website]\n* [http://www.thueringer-landtag.de/landtag/abgeordnete-und-fraktionen/abgeordnete/biografien/daten/87163/index.aspx Official Th\u00fcringer Landtag profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hocke, Bjorn}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Alternative for Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Landtag of Thuringia]]\n[[Category:People from L\u00fcnen]]\n[[Category:21st-century German politicians]]\n[[Category:German fascists]]\n", "name_user": "Thomstrijd", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed the vandalism of the extreme left.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bj%C3%B6rn_H%C3%B6cke"}
